# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: henri-dupuy-de-lôme
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p01] An **airship**, **dirigible balloon** or **dirigible** is a type of aerostat (lighter-than-air) aircraft that can navigate through the air flying under its own power.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p01] Aerostats use buoyancy from a lifting gas that is less dense than the surrounding air to achieve the lift needed to stay airborne.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p01] In early dirigibles, the lifting gas was hydrogen, due to its high lifting capacity and ready availability.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p01] Still, its inherent flammability led to several fatal accidents, rendering hydrogen airships obsolete.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p01] The alternative lifting gas, helium, is not flammable, but is rare and relatively expensive.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p01] Significant amounts were first discovered in the United States and for a while helium was only available for airship usage in North America.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p01] Most airships built since the 1960s have used helium, though some have used hot air.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p01] The bulk of an airship consists of the lighter-than-air *envelope*, which may either form the gasbag itself or contain some gas-filled cells.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p01] The engines, crew, and payload capacity necessary for the airship's operation are instead housed in the *gondola*, one or more enclosed platforms suspended below the envelope.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p01] The main types of airship are non-rigid, semi-rigid, and rigid airships.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p01] Non-rigid airships, often called "blimps", rely solely on internal gas pressure to maintain the envelope shape.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p01] Semi-rigid airships maintain their shape by internal pressure, but have some form of supporting structure, such as a fixed keel, attached to it.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p01] Rigid airships have an outer structural framework that maintains the shape and carries all structural loads, while the lifting gas is contained in one or more internal gasbags or cells.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p01] Rigid airships were first flown by Count Ferdinand von Zeppelin, and the vast majority of rigid airships built were manufactured by the firm he founded, Luftschiffbau Zeppelin.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p01] As a result, rigid airships are often called zeppelins.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p01] Airships were the first aircraft capable of controlled, powered flight and were most commonly used before the 1940s; their use declined as aeroplanes surpassed their capabilities.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p01] Their decline was accelerated by a series of high-profile accidents, including the 1930 crash and burning of the British R101 in France, the 1933 and 1935 storm-related crashes of the twin airborne aircraft carrier U.S.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p01] Navy helium-filled rigids, the USS *Akron* and USS *Macon* respectively, and the 1937 burning of the German hydrogen-filled *Hindenburg*.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p01] Since the 1960s, helium airships have been used where the ability to hover for extended periods outweighs the need for speed and manoeuverability, such as for advertising, tourism, camera platforms, geological surveys, and aerial observation.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p01] During the pioneer years of aeronautics, terms such as "airship", "air-ship", "air ship", and "ship of the air" were used to refer to any navigable or dirigible flying machine.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p01] In 1919 Frederick Handley Page was reported as referring to "ships of the air", with smaller passenger types as "air yachts".
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p01] In the 1930s, large intercontinental flying boats were also sometimes referred to as "ships of the air" or "flying-ships".
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p01] Nowadays, the term "airship" is used only for powered, dirigible balloons, with sub-types being classified as rigid, semi-rigid, or non-rigid.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p01] Semi-rigid architecture is the more recent, following advances in deformable structures and the exigency of reducing the weight and volume of the airships.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p01] They have a minimal structure that maintains the shape in concert with the overpressure of the gas envelope.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p01] An aerostat is an aircraft that remains aloft using buoyancy or static lift, as opposed to the aerodyne, which obtains lift by moving through the air.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p01] The term *aerostat* has also been used to indicate a tethered or moored balloon as opposed to a free-floating balloon.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p01] Aerostats today are capable of lifting a payload of 3,000 pounds (1,400 kg) to an altitude of more than 4.5 kilometres (2.8 mi) above sea level.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p01] They can also stay in the air for extended periods of time, particularly when powered by an on-board generator or if the tether contains electrical conductors.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p01] Because of this capability, aerostats can serve as platforms for telecommunications services.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p01] For instance, Platform Wireless International Corporation announced in 2001 that it would use a tethered 1,250 pounds (570 kg) airborne payload to deliver cellular phone service to a 140 miles (230 km) region in Brazil.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p01] The European Union's ABSOLUTE project was also reportedly exploring the use of tethered aerostat stations to provide telecommunications during disaster response.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p01] In British usage, it refers to any non-rigid aerostat, including barrage balloons and other kite balloons, having a streamlined shape and stabilising tail fins.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p01] Some blimps may be powered dirigibles, as in early versions of the Goodyear Blimp.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p01] Later Goodyear dirigibles, though technically *semi-rigid airships,* have still been called "blimps" by the company.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p01] The term zeppelin originally referred to airships manufactured by the German Zeppelin Company, which built and operated the first rigid airships in the early years of the twentieth century.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p01] The initials LZ, for *Luftschiff Zeppelin* (German for "Zeppelin airship"), were usually prefixed to their craft's serial identifiers.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p01] Streamlined rigid (or semi-rigid) airships are often referred to as "Zeppelins", because of the fame that this company acquired due to the number of airships it produced, although its early rival was the Parseval semi-rigid design.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p01] Hybrid airships fly with a positive aerostatic contribution, usually equal to the empty weight of the system, and the variable payload is sustained by propulsion or aerodynamic contribution.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p01] Airships are classified according to their method of construction into rigid, semi-rigid, and non-rigid types.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p01] A rigid airship has a rigid framework covered by an outer skin or envelope.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p01] The interior contains one or more gasbags, cells, or balloons to provide lift.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p01] Rigid airships are typically unpressurised and can be made to virtually any size.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p01] Most, but not all, of the German Zeppelin airships have been of this type.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p01] A semi-rigid airship has some supporting structure, but the main envelope is held in shape by the internal pressure of the lifting gas.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p01] Typically, the airship has an extended, usually articulated keel running along the bottom of the envelope to stop it kinking in the middle by distributing suspension loads into the envelope, while also allowing lower envelope pressures.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p01] Non-rigid airships are often called "blimps".
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p01] Most, but not all, of the American Goodyear airships have been blimps.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p01] A non-rigid airship relies entirely on internal gas pressure to retain its shape during flight.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p01] Unlike a rigid airship's gas envelope, the non-rigid airship's gas envelope has no compartments.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p01] However, it still typically has smaller internal bags containing air (ballonets).
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p01] As altitude increases, the lifting gas expands, and air from the ballonets is expelled through valves to maintain the hull's shape.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p01] To return to sea level, the process is reversed: air is forced back into the ballonets by scooping air from the engine exhaust and using auxiliary blowers.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p01] The envelope is the structure that contains the buoyant gas.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p01] Envelopes in the early 19th century were made from goldbeater's skin, selected for its low weight, relatively high strength, and impermeability compared to paper or linen.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p01] By the 1920s, natural rubber treated with cotton became the predominant elastomer used in envelope construction.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p01] Natural rubber was succeeded by neoprene in the 1930s and by Nylon and PET in the 1950s.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p01] The most successful of which is the Detroit ZMC-2, which logged 2265 hours of flight time from 1929 to 1941 before being scrapped, as it was considered too small for operational use on anti-submarine patrols.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p01] The problem of the exact determination of the pressure on an airship envelope is still problematic and has fascinated major scientists such as Theodor Von Karman.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p01] The envelope may contain ballonets (see below), allowing adjustment of the buoyant gas density by adding or removing envelope volume.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p01] A ballonet is an air bag inside the outer envelope of an airship, which, when inflated, reduces the volume available for the lifting gas, making it denser.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p01] Because air is denser than the lifting gas, inflating the ballonet reduces overall lift, while deflating it increases it.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p01] In this way, the ballonet can be used to adjust the lift as required by controlling the buoyancy.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p01] By inflating or deflating ballonets strategically, the pilot can control the airship's altitude and attitude.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p01] Ballonets may typically be used in non-rigid or semi-rigid airships, commonly with multiple ballonets located both fore and aft to maintain balance and to control the pitch of the airship.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p01] Lifting gas is generally hydrogen, helium, or hot air.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p01] Hydrogen provides the highest lift 1.1 kg/m3 (0.069 lb/cu ft) and is inexpensive and readily available, but is highly flammable and can detonate when mixed with air.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p01] Helium is completely non flammable, but gives lower performance-1.02 kg/m3 (0.064 lb/cu ft) and is a rare element and much more expensive.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p01] Thermal airships use a heated lifting gas, usually air, in a fashion similar to hot air balloons.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p01] The first to do so was flown in 1973 by the British company Cameron Balloons.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p01] Small airships carry their engine(s) in their gondola.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p01] Where there were multiple engines on larger airships, these were placed in separate nacelles, termed *power cars* or *engine cars*.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p01] To allow asymmetric thrust to be applied for maneuvering, these power cars were mounted towards the sides of the envelope, away from the centre line gondola.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p01] This also raised them above the ground, reducing the risk of a propeller strike when landing.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p01] Widely spaced power cars were also termed *wing cars*, from the use of "wing" to mean being on the side of something, as in a theater, rather than the aerodynamic device.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p01] These engine cars carried a crew during flight who maintained the engines as needed, but who also worked the engine controls, throttle, etc., mounted directly on the engine.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p01] Instructions were relayed to them from the pilot's station by a telegraph system, as on a ship.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p01] If fuel is burnt for propulsion, then a progressive reduction in the airship's overall weight occurs.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p01] In hydrogen airships, this is usually dealt with by simply venting cheap hydrogen lifting gas.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p01] In helium airships, water is often condensed from the exhaust and stored as ballast.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p01] To control the airship's direction and stability, it is equipped with fins and rudders.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p01] Fins are typically located on the tail section and provide stability and resistance to rolling.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p01] Rudders are movable surfaces on the tail that allow the pilot to steer the airship left or right.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p01] The empennage is the tail section of the airship, which includes the fins, rudders, and other aerodynamic surfaces.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p01] It plays a crucial role in maintaining stability and controlling the airship's attitude.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p01] Airships require a source of power to operate their propulsion systems.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p01] This includes engines, generators, or batteries, depending on the airship's type and design.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p01] Fuel tanks or batteries are typically located within the envelope or gondola.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p01] To navigate safely and communicate with ground control or other aircraft, airships are equipped with a range of instruments, including GPS systems, radios, radar, and navigation lights.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p01] Some airships have landing gear that allows them to land on runways or other surfaces.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p01] This landing gear may include wheels, skids, or landing pads.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p01] The main advantage of airships with respect to any other vehicle is that they require less energy to remain in flight, compared to other air vehicles.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p01] The proposed Varialift airship, powered by a mixture of solar-powered engines and conventional jet engines, would use only an estimated 8 percent of the fuel required by jet aircraft.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p01] Furthermore, utilizing the jet stream could allow for a faster and more energy-efficient cargo transport alternative to maritime shipping.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p01] This is one of the reasons why China has embraced their use recently.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] In 1670, the Jesuit Father Francesco Lana de Terzi, sometimes referred to as the "Father of Aeronautics", published a description of an "Aerial Ship" supported by four copper spheres from which the air was evacuated.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] Although the basic principle is sound, such a craft was unrealizable then and remains so to the present day, since external air pressure would cause the spheres to collapse unless their thickness were such as to make them too heavy to be buoyant.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] A hypothetical craft constructed using this principle is known as a *vacuum airship*.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] In 1709, the Brazilian-Portuguese Jesuit priest Bartolomeu de Gusmão made a hot-air balloon, the Passarola, ascend to the skies before an astonished Portuguese court.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] It would have been on August 8, 1709, when Father Bartolomeu de Gusmão held, in the courtyard of the Casa da Índia, in the city of Lisbon, the first Passarola demonstration.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] The balloon caught fire without leaving the ground, but, in a second demonstration, it rose to 95 meters in height.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] It was a small balloon of thick brown paper, filled with hot air, produced by the "fire of material contained in a clay bowl embedded in the base of a waxed wooden tray".
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] The event was witnessed by King John V of Portugal and the future Pope Innocent XIII.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] A more practical dirigible airship was described by Lieutenant Jean Baptiste Marie Meusnier in a paper entitled "*Mémoire sur l'équilibre des machines aérostatiques*" (Memorandum on the equilibrium of aerostatic machines) presented to the French Academy on 3 December 1783.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] The 16 watercolor drawings published the following year depict a 260-foot-long (79 m) streamlined envelope with internal ballonets that could be used for regulating lift: this was attached to a long carriage that could be used as a boat if the vehicle was forced to land in water.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] The airship was designed to be driven by three propellers and steered with a sail-like aft rudder.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] In 1784, Jean-Pierre Blanchard fitted a hand-powered propeller to a balloon, the first recorded means of propulsion carried aloft.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] In 1785, he crossed the English Channel in a balloon equipped with flapping wings for propulsion and a birdlike tail for steering.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] The 19th century saw continued attempts to add methods of propulsion to balloons.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] Rufus Porter built and flew scale models of his "Aerial Locomotive", but never a successful full-size implementation.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] The Australian William Bland sent designs for his "Atmotic airship" to the Great Exhibition held in London in 1851, where a model was displayed.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] This was an elongated balloon with a steam engine driving twin propellers suspended underneath.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] The balloon's lift was estimated at 5 tons, and the car with fuel at 3.5 tons, giving a payload of 1.5 tons.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] Bland believed that the machine could be driven at 80 km/h (50 mph) and could fly from Sydney to London in less than a week.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] In 1852, Henri Giffard became the first person to make an engine-powered flight when he flew 27 km (17 mi) in a steam-powered airship.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] Airships would develop considerably over the next two decades.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] In 1863, Solomon Andrews flew his aereon design, an unpowered, controllable dirigible in Perth Amboy, New Jersey, and offered the device to the U.S.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] He flew a later design in 1866 around New York City and as far as Oyster Bay, New York.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] This concept used changes in lift to provide propulsive force and did not need a powerplant.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] In 1872, the French naval architect Dupuy de Lôme launched a large navigable balloon, which was propelled by a propeller driven by eight men.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] It was developed during the Franco-Prussian war and was intended as an improvement to the balloons used for communications between Paris and the countryside during the siege of Paris, but was completed only after the end of the war.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] In 1872, Paul Haenlein flew an airship with an internal combustion engine running on the coal gas used to inflate the envelope, the first use of such an engine to power an aircraft.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] Ritchel made a public demonstration flight in 1878 of his hand-powered one-person rigid airship, and went on to build and sell five of his aircraft.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] Patent 154,654 "Apparatus for Navigating the Air".
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] It is believed successful trial flights were made between 1872 and 1874, but detailed dates are not available.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] The apparatus used a combination of wings and paddle wheels for navigation and propulsion.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] More details can be found in the book about his life.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] In 1883, the first electric-powered flight was made by Gaston Tissandier, who fitted a 1.5 hp (1.1 kW) Siemens electric motor to an airship.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] The first fully controllable free flight was made in 1884 by Charles Renard and Arthur Constantin Krebs in the French Army airship *La France*.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] La France made the first flight of an airship that landed where it took off; the 170 ft (52 m) long, 66,000 ft3 (1,900 m3) airship covered 8 km (5.0 mi) in 23 minutes with the aid of an 8.5 hp (6.3 kW) electric motor, and a 435 kg (959 lb) battery.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] In 1888, the design of the Campbell Air Ship, designed by Professor Peter C.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] Campbell, was built by the Novelty Air Ship Company.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] It was lost at sea in 1889 while being flown by Professor Hogan during an exhibition flight.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] From 1888 to 1897, Friedrich Wölfert built three airships powered by Daimler Motoren Gesellschaft-built petrol engines, the last of which, *Deutschland*, caught fire in flight and killed both occupants in 1897.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] The 1888 version used a 2 hp (1.5 kW) single cylinder Daimler engine and flew 10 km (6 mi) from Canstatt to Kornwestheim.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] In 1897, an airship with an aluminum envelope was built by the Hungarian-Croatian engineer David Schwarz.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] It made its first flight at Tempelhof field in Berlin after Schwarz had died.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] His widow, Melanie Schwarz, was paid 15,000 marks by Count Ferdinand von Zeppelin to release the industrialist Carl Berg from his exclusive contract to supply Schwartz with aluminium.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] From 1897 to 1899, Konstantin Danilewsky, a medical doctor and inventor from Kharkov, built four muscle-powered airships with a gas volume of 150–180 m3 (5,300–6,400 cu ft).
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] About 200 ascents were made within the framework of an experimental flight program, at two locations, with no significant incidents.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] In July 1900, the Luftschiff Zeppelin LZ1 made its first flight.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] This led to the most successful airships of all time: the Zeppelins, named after Count Ferdinand von Zeppelin, who began working on rigid airship designs in the 1890s, leading to the flawed LZ1 in 1900 and the more successful LZ2 in 1906.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] The Zeppelin airships had a framework composed of triangular lattice girders covered with fabric that contained separate gas cells.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] At first, multiplane tail surfaces were used for control and stability; later designs had simpler cruciform tail surfaces.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] The engines and crew were accommodated in "gondolas" hung beneath the hull, with driving propellers attached to the sides of the frame via long drive shafts.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] Additionally, there was a passenger compartment (later a bomb bay) located halfway between the two engine compartments.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] Alberto Santos-Dumont was a wealthy young Brazilian who lived in France and had a passion for flying.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] He designed 18 balloons and dirigibles before turning his attention to fixed-wing aircraft.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] On 19 October 1901, he flew his airship *Number 6*, from the Parc Saint Cloud to and around the Eiffel Tower and back in under thirty minutes.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] This feat earned him the Deutsch de la Meurthe prize of 100,000 francs.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] Many inventors were inspired by Santos-Dumont's small airships.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] Many airship pioneers, such as the American Thomas Scott Baldwin, financed their activities through passenger flights and public demonstration flights.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] Stanley Spencer built the first British airship with funds from advertising baby food on the sides of the envelope.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] Others, such as Walter Wellman and Melvin Vaniman, set their sights on loftier goals, attempting two polar flights in 1907 and 1909, and two trans-Atlantic flights in 1910 and 1912.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] On May 12, 1902, the inventor and Brazilian aeronaut Augusto Severo de Albuquerque Maranhao and his French mechanic, Georges Saché, died while flying over Paris in the airship Pax.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] A marble plaque at number 81 of the Avenue du Maine in Paris commemorates the location of Augusto Severo's accident.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] *The Catastrophe of the Balloon "Le Pax"* is a 1902 short silent film recreation of the catastrophe, directed by Georges Méliès.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] That same year, Spanish engineer Leonardo Torres Quevedo published the details of an innovative airship design in Spain and France, titled *Perfectionnements aux aerostats dirigibles*" ("Improvements in dirigible aerostats").
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] Featuring a non-rigid body with internal bracing wires—a system known as "auto-rigid"—it overcame the structural flaws of both rigid (Zeppelin-type) and flexible aircraft.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] This configuration provided greater flight stability, enabling the use of heavier engines and a higher passenger capacity.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] In 1905, assisted by Captain Alfredo Kindelán, Torres built the airship *Torres Quevedo* at the Guadalajara military base.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] He patented an improved design in 1909 and offered it to the French Astra company, which began mass production in 1911 as the Astra-Torres airship.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] Torres also designed a docking station to resolve the technical challenges of mooring dirigibles.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] In 1910, he proposed securing the nose of an airship to a mooring mast, allowing the craft to weathervane as wind direction changed.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] This ground-erected metal column allowed airships to be moored in the open at any time, regardless of wind speed.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] Additionally, his design improved the accessibility of temporary landing sites for passenger disembarkation.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] He filed the final patent in Belgium in February 1911, and later in France and the United Kingdom in 1912, under the title "Improvements in Mooring Arrangements for Airships".
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] In Britain, the Army built its first dirigible, the *Nulli Secundus*, in 1907.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] The Navy ordered the construction of an experimental rigid in 1908.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] Officially known as His Majesty's Airship No.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] 1 and nicknamed the *Mayfly*, it broke its back in 1911 before making a single flight.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] Work on a successor did not start until 1913.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] The German airship passenger service, known as DELAG (Deutsche-Luftschiffahrts AG), was established in 1910.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] The prospect of airships as bombers had been recognized in Europe well before the airships were up to the task.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] Wells's *The War in the Air* (1908) described the obliteration of entire fleets and cities by airship attack.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] The Italian forces became the first to use dirigibles for military purposes during the Italo–Turkish War, with the first bombing mission flown on 10 March 1912.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] World War I marked the airship's real debut as a weapon.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] The Germans, French, and Italians all used airships for scouting and tactical bombing early in the war, and all learned that airships were too vulnerable for operations over the front.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] The decision to end operations in direct support of armies was made by all in 1917.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] Many in the German military believed they had found the ideal weapon to counter British naval superiority and strike at Britain itself.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] In contrast, more realistic airship advocates believed the zeppelin's value lay in its role as a long-range scout-and-attack craft for naval operations.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] Raids on England began in January 1915 and peaked in 1916; following losses to British defences, only a few raids were conducted in 1917–18, the last in August 1918.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] Zeppelins proved to be terrifying but inaccurate weapons.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] Navigation, target selection, and bomb-aiming proved to be difficult under the best of conditions, and the cloud cover that was frequently encountered by the airships reduced accuracy even further.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] The physical damage done by airships over the course of the war was insignificant, and the deaths that they caused amounted to a few hundred.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] Nevertheless, the raids caused a significant diversion of British resources to defense efforts.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] The airships were initially immune to attack by aircraft and anti-aircraft guns: as the pressure in their envelopes was only just higher than ambient air, holes had little effect.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] But following the introduction of a combination of incendiary and explosive ammunition in 1916, their flammable hydrogen lifting gas made them vulnerable to the defending aeroplanes.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] Several were shot down in flames by British defenders, and many others were destroyed in accidents.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] New designs capable of reaching greater altitudes were developed, but while this made them immune to attack, it also worsened their bombing accuracy.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] Countermeasures by the British included sound detection equipment, searchlights, and anti-aircraft artillery, followed by night fighters in 1915.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] One tactic used early in the war, when their limited range meant the airships had to fly from forward bases and the only zeppelin production facilities were in Friedrichshafen, was the British Royal Naval Air Service's bombing of airship sheds.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] Later in the war, the development of the aircraft carrier led to the first successful carrier-based air strike in history: on the morning of 19 July 1918, seven Sopwith 2F.1 Camels were launched from HMS *Furious* and struck the airship base at Tønder, destroying zeppelins L 54 and L 60.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] The British Army had abandoned airship development in favour of aeroplanes before the start of the war, but the Royal Navy had recognized the need for small airships to counteract the submarine and mine threat in coastal waters.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] Beginning in February 1915, they began to develop the SS (Sea Scout) class of blimp.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] These had a small envelope of 1,699–1,982 m3 (60,000–70,000 ft3) and at first used aircraft fuselages without the wing and tail surfaces as control cars.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] Later, more advanced blimps with purpose-built gondolas were used.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] The NS class (North Sea) were the largest and most effective non-rigid airships in British service, with a gas capacity of 10,200 m3 (360,000 ft3), a crew of 10, and an endurance of 24 hours.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] Six 230 lb (100 kg) bombs were carried, as well as three to five machine guns.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] British blimps were used for scouting, mine clearance, and convoy patrol duties.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] During the war, the British operated over 200 non-rigid airships.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] Several were sold to Russia, France, the United States, and Italy.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] The large number of trained crews, low attrition rate, and constant experimentation in handling techniques meant that at the war's end, Britain was the world leader in non-rigid airship technology.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] The Royal Navy continued the development of rigid airships until the end of the war.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] Eight rigid airships had been completed by the armistice (No.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] 9r, four 23 Class, two R23X Class, and one R31 Class), although several more were in an advanced state of completion by the war's end.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] Both France and Italy continued to use airships throughout the war.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] France preferred the non-rigid type, whereas Italy flew 49 semi-rigid airships in both the scouting and bombing roles.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] Aeroplanes had almost entirely replaced airships as bombers by the end of the war, and Germany's remaining zeppelins were destroyed by their crews, scrapped, or handed over to the Allied powers as war reparations.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] The British rigid airship program, which had mainly been a reaction to the potential threat of the German airships, was wound down.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] Britain, the United States, and Germany built rigid airships between the two world wars.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] Italy and France made limited use of Zeppelins handed over as war reparations.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] Italy, the Soviet Union, the United States, and Japan mainly operated semi-rigid airships.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] Under the terms of the Treaty of Versailles, Germany was not allowed to build airships of greater capacity than a million cubic feet.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] On May 12, 1926, the Italian-built semi-rigid airship *Norge* was the first aircraft to fly over the North Pole.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] The British R33 and R34 were improved versions of the German L 33, which had come down almost intact in Yorkshire on 24 September 1916.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] Despite being almost three years out of date by the time they were launched in 1919, they became two of the most successful airships in British service.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] The creation of the Royal Air Force (RAF) in early 1918 created a hybrid British airship program.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] The RAF was not interested in airships, while the Admiralty was, so a deal was made in which the Admiralty would design any future military airships and the RAF would handle workforce, facilities, and operations.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] On 2 July 1919, R34 began the first crossing of the Atlantic by a passenger aircraft.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] It landed at Mineola, Long Island on 6 July after 108 hours in the air; the return crossing began on 8 July and took 75 hours.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] This feat failed to generate enthusiasm for continued airship development, and the British airship program was rapidly wound down.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] Navy acquired its first airship, the DH-1, but it was destroyed while being inflated shortly after delivery to the Navy.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] Navy contracted to buy the R 38, which was being built in Britain, but before it was handed over, it was destroyed because of a structural failure during a test flight.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] America then started constructing the USS *Shenandoah*, designed by the Bureau of Aeronautics and based on the Zeppelin L 49.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] 1 and first flown on 4 September 1923 at Lakehurst, New Jersey, it was the first airship to be inflated with the noble gas helium, which was then so scarce that the *Shenandoah* contained most of the world's supply.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] A second airship, USS *Los Angeles*, was built by the Zeppelin company as compensation for the airships that should have been handed over as war reparations according to the terms of the Versailles Treaty but had been sabotaged by their crews.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] This construction order saved the Zeppelin works from the threat of closure.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] The success of the *Los Angeles*, which was flown successfully for eight years, encouraged the U.S.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] Navy to invest in its own, larger airships.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] When the *Los Angeles* was delivered, the two airships had to share the limited supply of helium, and thus alternated operating and overhauls.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] In 1922, Sir Dennistoun Burney suggested a plan for a subsidised air service throughout the British Empire using airships (the Burney Scheme).
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] Following the coming to power of Ramsay MacDonald's Labour government in 1924, the scheme was transformed into the Imperial Airship Scheme, under which two airships were built, one by a private company and the other by the Royal Airship Works under Air Ministry control.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] The two designs were radically different.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] The "capitalist" ship, the *R100*, was more conventional, while the "socialist" ship, the R101, had many innovative design features.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] Construction of both took longer than expected, and the airships did not fly until 1929.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] Neither airship was capable of the service intended, though the R100 did complete a proving flight to Canada and back in 1930.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] On 5 October 1930, the R101, which had not been thoroughly tested after major modifications, crashed on its maiden voyage to India at Beauvais in France, killing 48 of the 54 people aboard.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] Among the dead were the craft's chief designer and the Secretary of State for Air.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] The disaster ended British interest in airships.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] In 1925 the Zeppelin company started construction of the *Graf Zeppelin* (LZ 127), the largest airship that could be built in the company's existing shed, and intended to stimulate interest in passenger airships.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] The *Graf Zeppelin* burned *blau gas*, similar to propane, stored in large gas bags below the hydrogen cells, as fuel.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] Since its density was similar to that of air, it avoided the weight change as fuel was used, and thus the need to valve hydrogen.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] The *Graf Zeppelin* had an impressive safety record, flying over 1,600,000 km (990,000 mi) (including the first circumnavigation of the globe by airship) without a single passenger injury.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] Navy experimented with using airships as airborne aircraft carriers, building on a concept pioneered by the British.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] The USS *Los Angeles* was used for initial experiments, and the USS *Akron* and *Macon*, the world's largest at the time, were used to test the principle in naval operations.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] Each carried four F9C Sparrowhawk fighters in its hangar, and could carry a fifth on the trapeze.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] By the time the Navy began developing a sound doctrine for using the ZRS-type airships, the last of the two built, USS *Macon*, had been wrecked.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] Meanwhile, the seaplane had become more capable and was considered a better investment.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] Navy lost all three U.S.-built rigid airships to accidents.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] USS *Shenandoah* flew into a severe thunderstorm over Noble County, Ohio while on a poorly planned publicity flight on 3 September 1925.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] It broke into pieces, killing 14 of its crew.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] USS *Akron* was caught in a severe storm and flown into the surface of the sea off the shore of New Jersey on 3 April 1933.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] It carried no lifeboats and few life vests, so 73 of its crew of 76 died from drowning or hypothermia.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] USS *Macon* was lost after suffering a structural failure offshore near Point Sur Lighthouse on 12 February 1935.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] The failure caused a loss of gas, which was exacerbated when the aircraft was flown over pressure height, causing it to lose too much helium to maintain flight.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] Only two of its crew of 83 died in the crash thanks to the inclusion of life jackets and inflatable rafts after the *Akron* disaster.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] The Empire State Building was completed in 1931 with a dirigible mast, in anticipation of future passenger airship service, but no airship ever used the mast.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] Various entrepreneurs experimented with airship-based commuting and freight shipping.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] In the 1930s, the German Zeppelins successfully competed with other means of transport.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] They could carry significantly more passengers than other contemporary aircraft while providing amenities similar to those on ocean liners, such as private cabins, observation decks, and dining rooms.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] Less importantly, the technology was potentially more energy-efficient than heavier-than-air designs.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] Zeppelins were also faster than ocean liners.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] On the other hand, operating airships was quite involved.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] Often, the crew would outnumber passengers, and on the ground, large teams were necessary to assist mooring, and very large hangars were required at airports.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] By the mid-1930s, only Germany still pursued airship development.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] The Zeppelin company continued to operate the *Graf Zeppelin* on passenger service between Frankfurt and Recife in Brazil, taking 68 hours.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] Even with the small *Graf Zeppelin*, the operation was almost profitable.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] In the mid-1930s, work began on an airship designed specifically to operate a passenger service across the Atlantic.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] The *Hindenburg* (LZ 129) completed a successful 1936 season, carrying passengers between Lakehurst, New Jersey and Germany.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] The year 1937 started with the most spectacular and widely remembered airship accident.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] Approaching the Lakehurst mooring mast minutes before landing on 6 May 1937, the *Hindenburg* suddenly burst into flames and crashed to the ground.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] Of the 97 people aboard, 35 died: 13 passengers, 22 aircrew, along with one American ground-crewman.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] The disaster occurred before a large crowd and was filmed, and a radio news reporter was recording the arrival.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] This was a disaster that theater goers could see and hear in newsreels.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] The *Hindenburg* disaster shattered public confidence in airships and brought a definitive end to their "golden age".
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] The day after the *Hindenburg* disaster, the *Graf Zeppelin* landed safely in Germany after its return flight from Brazil.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] This was the last international passenger airship flight.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] Development of airships continued only in the United States and, to a lesser extent, in the Soviet Union.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] The Soviet Union had several semi-rigid and non-rigid airships.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] The semi-rigid dirigible SSSR-V6 OSOAVIAKhIM was among the largest of these craft, and it set the longest endurance flight at the time of over 130 hours.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] It crashed into a mountain in 1938, killing 13 of the 19 people on board.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] Although this was a severe blow to the Soviet airship program, the Soviets continued to operate non-rigid airships until 1950.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] While Germany determined that airships were obsolete for military purposes in the coming war and concentrated on developing aeroplanes, the United States pursued a program of military airship construction even though it had not developed a clear military doctrine for airship use.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] When the Japanese attacked Pearl Harbor on 7 December 1941, bringing the United States into World War II, the U.S.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] Only *K*- and *TC*-class airships were suitable for combat, and they were quickly pressed into service against Japanese and German submarines, which were then sinking American shipping within visual range of the American coast.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] Navy command, remembering airship's anti-submarine success in World War I, immediately requested new modern antisubmarine airships and on 2 January 1942 formed the ZP-12 patrol unit based in Lakehurst from the four *K* airships.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] The ZP-32 patrol unit was formed from two *TC* and two *L* airships a month later, based at NAS Moffett Field in Sunnyvale, California.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] An airship training base was created there as well.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] The status of submarine-hunting Goodyear airships in the early days of World War II has created significant confusion.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] Although various accounts refer to airships *Resolute* and *Volunteer* as operating as "privateers" under a Letter of Marque, Congress never authorized a commission, nor did the President sign one.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] In 1942–44, approximately 1,400 airship pilots and 3,000 support crew members were trained in the military airship crew training program, and the number of airship military personnel grew from 430 to 12,400.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] The U.S. airships were produced by the Goodyear factory in Akron, Ohio.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] From 1942 to 1945, 154 airships were built for the U.S.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] Navy (133 *K*-class, 10 *L*-class, seven *G*-class, four *M*-class) and five *L*-class for civilian customers (serial numbers *L-4* to *L-8*).
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] The primary airship tasks were patrol and convoy escort near the American coastline.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] They also served as an organization centre for convoys, directing ship movements, and were used in naval search-and-rescue operations.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] Rarer duties of the airships included aerophotography reconnaissance, naval mine-laying and mine-sweeping, parachute unit transport and deployment, and cargo and personnel transportation.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] They were deemed quite successful in their duties with the highest combat readiness factor in the entire U.S.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] During the war, some 532 ships without airship escort were sunk near the U.S. coast by enemy submarines.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] Only one ship, the tanker *Persephone*, of the 89,000 or so in convoys escorted by blimps was sunk by the enemy.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] Airships engaged submarines with depth charges and, less frequently, with other on-board weapons.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] They were excellent at driving submarines down, where their limited speed and range prevented them from attacking convoys.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] The weapons available to airships were so limited that until the advent of the homing torpedo, they had little chance of sinking a submarine.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] Only one airship was ever destroyed by a U-boat: on the night of 18/19 July 1943, the *K-74* from ZP-21 division was patrolling the coastline near Florida.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] Using radar, the airship located a surfaced German submarine.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] The *K-74* made her attack run, but the U-boat opened fire first.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] *K-74*'s depth charges did not release as she crossed the U-boat, and the *K-74* received serious damage, losing gas pressure and an engine, but landing in the water without loss of life.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] The crew was rescued by patrol boats in the morning, but one crewman, Aviation Machinist's Mate Second Class Isadore Stessel, died from a shark attack.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] The U-boat, *submarine U-134*, was slightly damaged and the next day or so was attacked by aircraft, sustaining damage that forced it to return to base.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] It was finally sunk on 24 August 1943 by a British Vickers Wellington near Vigo, Spain.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] Fleet Airship Wing One operated from Lakehurst, New Jersey, Glynco, Georgia, Weeksville, North Carolina, South Weymouth NAS, Massachusetts, Brunswick NAS, and Bar Harbor, Maine, Yarmouth, Nova Scotia, and Argentia, Newfoundland.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] Some Navy blimps saw action in the European theater of war.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] Navy moved an entire squadron of eight Goodyear K class blimps (K-89, K-101, K-109, K-112, K-114, K-123, K-130, & K-134) with flight and maintenance crews from Weeksville Naval Air Station in North Carolina to Naval Air Station Port Lyautey, French Morocco.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] Their mission was to locate and destroy German U-boats in the relatively shallow waters around the Strait of Gibraltar where magnetic anomaly detection (MAD) was viable.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] PBY aircraft had been searching these waters, but MAD required low-altitude flying that was dangerous at night.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] The blimps were considered a perfect solution to establish a 24/7 MAD barrier (fence) at the Straits of Gibraltar with the PBYs flying the day shift and the blimps flying the night shift.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] The first two blimps (K-123 & K-130) left South Weymouth NAS on 28 May 1944 and flew to Argentia, Newfoundland, the Azores, and finally to Port Lyautey where they completed the first transatlantic crossing by nonrigid airships on 1 June 1944.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] The blimps of USN Blimp Squadron ZP-14 (Blimpron 14, aka *The Africa Squadron*) also conducted mine-spotting and mine-sweeping operations in key Mediterranean ports and various escorts, including the convoy carrying United States President Franklin D.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] Roosevelt and British Prime Minister Winston Churchill to the Yalta Conference in 1945.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] Airships from the ZP-12 unit took part in the sinking of the last U-boat before German capitulation, sinking the *U-881* on 6 May 1945 together with destroyers USS Atherton and USS Moberly.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] Other airships patrolled the Caribbean, Fleet Airship Wing Two, Headquartered at Naval Air Station Richmond, covered the Gulf of Mexico from Richmond and Key West, Florida, Houma, Louisiana, as well as Hitchcock and Brownsville, Texas.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] FAW 2 also patrolled the northern Caribbean from San Julian, the Isle of Pines (now called Isla de la Juventud) and Guantánamo Bay, Cuba, as well as Vernam Field, Jamaica.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] Navy blimps of Fleet Airship Wing Five, (ZP-51) operated from bases in Trinidad, British Guiana and Paramaribo, Suriname.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] Fleet Airship Wing Four operated along the coast of Brazil.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] Two squadrons, VP-41 and VP-42 flew from bases at Amapá, Igarapé-Açu, São Luís Fortaleza, Fernando de Noronha, Recife, Maceió, Ipitanga (near Salvador, Bahia), Caravelas, Vitória and the hangar built for the *Graf Zeppelin* at Santa Cruz, Rio de Janeiro.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] Fleet Airship Wing Three operated squadrons, ZP-32 from Moffett Field, ZP-31 at NAS Santa Ana, and ZP-33 at NAS Tillamook, Oregon.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] Auxiliary fields were at Del Mar, Lompoc, Watsonville and Eureka, California, North Bend and Astoria, Oregon, as well as Shelton and Quillayute in Washington.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] From 2 January 1942 until the end of war airship operations in the Atlantic, the blimps of the Atlantic fleet made 37,554 flights and flew 378,237 hours.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] Of the over 70,000 ships in convoys protected by blimps, only one was sunk by a submarine while under blimp escort.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] The Soviet Union flew a single airship during the war.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] The *USSR-V1* (also known as the SSSR-V1 or the CCCP-B1) was originally built in 1932. and rebuilt in 1942 as the *USSR-V12*.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] The V12 entered service in 1942 for hydrogen delivery, paratrooper training, and equipment transport.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] It made 1432 flights with 300 metric tons of cargo until 1945.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] In 1947, the V12 crashed into the shed doors, catching fire.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] It was rebuilt and re-commissioned, as the *USSR-V12bis* *Patriot*, in the same year.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] On 1 February 1945, the Soviets commissioned a second airship, *Pobyeda* (*Victory*).
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] The Pobyeda was used for mine-sweeping and wreckage clearing in the Black Sea, crashing on 29 January 1947.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] Although airships are no longer used for major cargo and passenger transport, they are still used for other purposes such as advertising, sightseeing, surveillance, research, and advocacy.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] There were several studies and proposals for nuclear-powered airships, starting with a 1954 study by F.W.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] Kirschner published the book *The Zeppelin in the Atomic Age*, which promoted the use of atomic airships.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] In 1959, Goodyear presented a plan for a nuclear-powered airship for both military and commercial use.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] Several other proposals and papers were published during the next decades.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] In the 1980s, Per Lindstrand and his team introduced the *GA-42* airship, the first airship to use fly-by-wire flight control, which considerably reduced the pilot's workload.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] An airship was prominently featured in the James Bond film *A View to a Kill*, released in 1985.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] The Skyship 500 had the livery of Zorin Industries.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] The world's largest thermal airship (300,000 cubic feet; 8,500 cubic metres) was constructed by the Per Lindstrand company for French botanists in 1993.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] The *AS-300* carried an underslung raft, which the airship positioned atop tree canopies in the rain forest, allowing the botanists to conduct their treetop research without causing significant damage to the rainforest.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] When research was finished at a given location, the airship returned to pick up and relocate the raft.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] Navy awarded a US$168.9 million contract to Westinghouse Electric and Airship Industries of the UK to find out whether an airship could be used as an airborne platform to detect the threat of sea-skimming missiles, such as the Exocet.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] At 2.5 million cubic feet, the Westinghouse/Airship Industries Sentinel 5000 (Redesignated YEZ-2A by the U.S.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] Navy) prototype design was to have been the largest blimp ever constructed.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] Additional funding for the Naval Airship Program was killed in 1995 and development was discontinued.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] The SVAM CA-80 airship, produced in 2000 by Shanghai Vantage Airship Manufacture Co., Ltd., conducted a successful trial flight in September 2001.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] This was designed for advertisement and propagation, air photography, scientific testing, tours, and surveillance duties.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] It was certified as a grade-A Hi-Tech introduction program (No.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] The CAAC granted type design approval and a certificate of airworthiness for the airship.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] In the 1990s, the Zeppelin company returned to the airship business.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] Their new model, designated the Zeppelin NT, made its maiden flight on 18 September 1997.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] As of 2009 there were four NT aircraft flying; a fifth was completed in March 2009, and an expanded NT-14 (14,000 cubic meters of helium, capable of carrying 19 passengers) was under construction.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] One was sold to a Japanese company, and was planned to be flown to Japan in the summer of 2004.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] Due to delays getting permission from the Russian government, the company decided to transport the airship to Japan by sea.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] One of the four NT craft is in South Africa carrying diamond detection equipment from De Beers, an application at which the very stable, low-vibration NT platform excels.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] The project included design adaptations for high-temperature operation and desert climates, as well as a separate mooring mast and a very heavy mooring truck.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] NT-4 belonged to Airship Ventures of Moffett Field in Mountain View, San Francisco Bay Area, and provided sightseeing tours.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] Blimps are used for advertising and as TV camera platforms at major sporting events.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] The most iconic of these are the Goodyear Blimps.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] Goodyear operates three blimps in the United States, and The Lightship Group, now The AirSign Airship Group, operates up to 19 advertising blimps around the world.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] Airship Management Services owns and operates three Skyship 600 blimps.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] Two operate as advertising and security ships in North America and the Caribbean.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] Airship Ventures operated a Zeppelin NT for advertising, passenger service, and special mission projects.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] They were the only airship operator in the U.S. authorized to fly commercial passengers until they closed their doors in 2012.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] Skycruise Switzerland AG owns and operates two Skyship 600 blimps.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] One operates regularly over Switzerland and is used on sightseeing tours.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] The Switzerland-based Skyship 600 has also played other roles over the years.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] For example, it was flown over Athens during the 2004 Summer Olympics as a security measure.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] In November 2006, it carried advertising calling it *The Spirit of Dubai* as it began a publicity tour from London to Dubai, UAE on behalf of The Palm Islands, the world's largest artificial islands created as a residential complex.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] Los Angeles-based Worldwide Aeros Corp. produces FAA Type Certified Aeros 40D Sky Dragon airships.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] Navy began to fly airships again after a hiatus of nearly 44 years.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] The program uses a single American Blimp Company A-170 nonrigid airship, with designation MZ-3A.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] Operations focus on crew training and research, and the platform integrator is Northrop Grumman.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] The program is directed by the Naval Air Systems Command and is being carried out at NAES Lakehurst, the original centre of U.S.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] Navy lighter-than-air operations in previous decades.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] Army bought an A380+ airship from American Blimp Corporation through a systems-level contract with Northrop Grumman and Booz Allen Hamilton.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] The airship started flight tests in late 2007, with a primary goal of carrying 2,500 lb (1,100 kg) of payload to an altitude of 15,000 ft (4,600 m) under remote control and autonomous waypoint navigation.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] The program will also demonstrate carrying 1,000 lb (450 kg) of payload to 20,000 ft (6,100 m) The platform could be used for intelligence collection.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] In 2008, the *CA-150* airship was launched by Vantage Airship.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] This is an improved version of the model *CA-120*, and was completed in 2008.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] With larger volume and increased passenger capacity, it is the largest manned nonrigid airship in China at present.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] In late June 2014 the Electronic Frontier Foundation flew the GEFA-FLUG AS 105 GD/4 blimp AE Bates (owned by, and in conjunction with, Greenpeace) over the NSA's Bluffdale Utah Data Center in protest.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] Hybrid designs such as the Heli-Stat airship/helicopter, the Aereon aerostatic/aerodynamic craft, and the CycloCrane (a hybrid aerostatic/rotorcraft) struggled to take flight.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] The Cyclocrane was also interesting because the airship's envelope rotated about its longitudinal axis.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] In 2005, a short-lived project of the U.S.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency (DARPA) was Walrus HULA, which explored the potential of using airships as long-distance, heavy-lift craft.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] The primary goal of the research program was to determine the feasibility of building an airship capable of carrying 500 short tons (450 t) of payload a distance of 12,000 mi (19,000 km) and land on an unimproved location without the use of external ballast or ground equipment (such as masts).
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] In 2005, two contractors, Lockheed Martin and US Aeros Airships, were each awarded approximately $3 million to conduct feasibility studies on WALRUS designs.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p02] Congress removed funding for Walrus HULA in 2006.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] Army awarded a $517 million (£350.6 million) contract to Northrop Grumman and partner Hybrid Air Vehicles to develop a Long Endurance Multi-Intelligence Vehicle (LEMV) system consisting of three HAV 304s.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] The project was cancelled in February 2012 due to it being behind schedule and over budget; also the forthcoming U.S. withdrawal from Afghanistan where it was intended to be deployed.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] Following this the Hybrid Air Vehicles HAV 304 Airlander 10 was repurchased by Hybrid Air Vehicles then modified and reassembled in Bedford, UK, and renamed the Airlander 10.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] As of 2018, it was being tested in readiness for its UK flight test programme.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] A-NSE, a French company, manufactures and operates airships and aerostats.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] For 2 years, A-NSE has been testing its airships for the French Army.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] Airships and aerostats are operated to provide intelligence, surveillance, and reconnaissance (ISR) support.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] Their airships include many innovative features, such as water-ballast take-off and landing systems, variable-geometry envelopes, and thrust–vectoring systems.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] The U.S. government has funded two major projects in the high altitude arena.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] The Composite Hull High Altitude Powered Platform (CHHAPP) is sponsored by U.S.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] This aircraft is also sometimes called the *HiSentinel High-Altitude Airship*.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] This prototype ship made a five-hour test flight in September 2005.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] The second project, the high-altitude airship (HAA), is sponsored by DARPA.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] In 2005, DARPA awarded a contract worth nearly $150 million to Lockheed Martin for prototype development.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] The first flight of the HAA was planned for 2008 but was delayed due to programmatic and funding issues.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] The HAA project evolved into the High Altitude Long Endurance-Demonstrator (HALE-D).
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] Army and Lockheed Martin launched the first-of-its-kind HALE-D on July 27, 2011.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] After attaining an altitude of 32,000 ft (9,800 m), due to an anomaly, the company decided to abort the mission.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] The airship made a controlled descent in an unpopulated area of southwest Pennsylvania.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] On 31 January 2006, Lockheed Martin made the first flight of their secretly built hybrid airship designated the P-791.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] The design is very similar to the SkyCat, unsuccessfully promoted for many years by the British company Advanced Technologies Group (ATG).
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] Dirigibles have been used in the War in Afghanistan for reconnaissance purposes, as they enable constant monitoring of a specific area via cameras mounted on the airships.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] In the 1990s, the successor to the original Zeppelin company in Friedrichshafen, the *Zeppelin Luftschifftechnik GmbH*, resumed airship construction.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] The first experimental craft (later christened *Friedrichshafen*) of the type "Zeppelin NT" flew in September 1997.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] Though larger than common blimps, the *Neue Technologie* (New Technology) zeppelins are much smaller than their giant ancestors and not actually Zeppelin-types in the classical sense.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] Apart from the greater payload, their main advantages compared to blimps are higher speed and excellent maneuverability.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] Meanwhile, several *Zeppelin NT* have been produced and operated profitably in joyrides, research flights, and similar applications.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] In June 2004, a Zeppelin NT was sold for the first time to a Japanese company, Nippon Airship Corporation, for tourism and advertising mainly around Tokyo.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] It was also given a role at the 2005 Expo in Aichi.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] The aircraft began a flight from Friedrichshafen to Japan, stopping at Geneva, Paris, Rotterdam, Munich, Berlin, Stockholm, and other European cities to carry passengers on short legs of the flight.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] Russian authorities denied overflight permission, so the airship had to be dismantled and shipped to Japan rather than following the historic *Graf Zeppelin* flight from Germany to Japan.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] In 2008, Airship Ventures Inc. began operations from Moffett Federal Airfield near Mountain View, California and, until November 2012, offered tours of the San Francisco Bay Area for up to 12 passengers.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] In November 2005, De Beers, a diamond mining company, launched an airship exploration program over the remote Kalahari Desert.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] A Zeppelin NT, equipped with a Bell Geospace gravity gradiometer, was used to find potential diamond mines by scanning the local geography for low-density rock formations, known as kimberlite pipes.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] On 21 September 2007, the airship was severely damaged by a whirlwind while in Botswana.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] One crew member, who was on watch aboard the moored craft, was slightly injured but released after overnight observation in the hospital.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] Several companies, such as Cameron Balloons in Bristol, United Kingdom, build hot-air airships.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] These combine the structures of both hot-air balloons and small airships.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] The envelope is the normal cigar shape, complete with tail fins, but is inflated with hot air instead of helium to provide the lifting force.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] A small gondola, carrying the pilot and passengers, a small engine, and the burners to provide the hot air, is suspended below the envelope, beneath an opening through which the burners protrude.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] Hot-air airships typically cost less to buy and maintain than modern helium-based blimps, and can be quickly deflated after flights.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] This makes them easy to carry in trailers or trucks and inexpensive to store.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] They are usually very slow-moving, with a typical top speed of 25–30 km/h (16–19 mph; 6.9–8.3 m/s).
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] They are mainly used for advertising, but at least one has been used in rainforests for wildlife observation, as they can be easily transported to remote areas.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] Remote-controlled (RC) airships, a type of unmanned aerial system (UAS), are sometimes used for commercial purposes, such as advertising and aerial video and photography, as well as for recreational purposes.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] They are particularly common as an advertising mechanism at indoor stadiums.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] While RC airships are sometimes flown outdoors, doing so for commercial purposes is illegal in the US.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] Commercial use of an uncrewed airship must be certified under part 121.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] In 2008, French adventurer Stephane Rousson [Fr] attempted to cross the English Channel with a muscular pedal-powered airship.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] Stephane Rousson also flies the Aérosail, a sky sailing yacht [Fr].
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] Today, with large, fast, and more cost-efficient fixed-wing aircraft and helicopters, it is unknown whether huge airships can operate profitably in regular passenger transport.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] However, as energy costs rise, attention is once again returning to these lighter-than-air vessels as a possible alternative.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] At the very least, the idea of comparatively slow, "majestic" cruising at relatively low altitudes and in a comfortable atmosphere certainly has retained some appeal.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] It has periodically been suggested that airships could be employed for cargo transport, especially for delivering extremely heavy loads over great distances to areas with poor infrastructure.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] This has also been called roadless trucking.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] Also, airships could be used for heavy lifting over short distances (e.g., on construction sites); this is described as heavy-lift, short-haul.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] In both cases, the airships would be heavy haulers.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] The old Zeppelins already faced the challenge of maintaining buoyancy when large amounts of fuel were burnt on long, often intercontinental, trips.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] Letting go lifting gas would be an expensive option.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] Another idea was to pick up water as ballast from the sea or from exhaust fumes.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] A third was using a kind of lift gas that could be burnt, like Blau gas, as a Buoyancy compensator.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] The matter is even worse when heavy freight is delivered.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] One recent (1996 to 2002) enterprise of this sort was the German *Cargolifter* project, in which a hybrid (thus not entirely Zeppelin-type) airship, even larger than *Hindenburg*, was proposed.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] Around 2000, CargoLifter AG built the world's largest self-supporting hall, measuring 360 m (1,180 ft) long, 210 m (690 ft) wide and 107 m (351 ft) high about 60 km (37 mi) south of Berlin.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] In May 2002, the project was stopped for financial reasons; the company had to file bankruptcy.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] The enormous CargoLifter hangar was later converted to house the Tropical Islands Resort.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] Cargolifter had intended to replace its cargo upon delivery with water-filled containers of the same weight.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] Although no rigid airships are currently used for heavy lifting, hybrid airships are being developed for such purposes.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] AEREON 26, tested in 1971, was described in John McPhee's *The Deltoid Pumpkin Seed*.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] Flying Whales is a French aeronautic start-up developing an airship for transporting heavy loads.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] An impediment to the large-scale development of airships as heavy haulers has been determining how to use them cost-efficiently.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] To have a significant economic advantage over ocean transport, cargo airships must deliver their payload faster than ocean carriers but more cheaply than airplanes.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] William Crowder, a fellow at the Logistics Management Institute, has calculated that cargo airships are only economical when they can transport 500 to 1,000 tons, approximately the same as a super-jumbo aircraft.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] The large initial investment required to build such a large airship has been a hindrance to production, especially given the risk inherent in a new technology.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] The chief commercial officer of the company, hoping to sell the LMH-1, a cargo airship developed by Lockheed Martin, believes that airships can be economical in hard-to-reach locations such as mining operations in northern Canada that currently require ice roads.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] A metal-clad airship has a very thin metal envelope, rather than the usual fabric.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] The shell may be either internally braced or monocoque as in the ZMC-2, which flew many times in the 1920s, the only example ever to do so.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] The shell may be gas-tight, as in a non-rigid blimp, or the design may employ internal gas bags, as in a rigid airship.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] Compared to a fabric envelope, the metal cladding is expected to be more durable.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] A Hybrid airship is an aircraft that combines characteristics of heavier-than-air (aeroplane or helicopter) and lighter-than-air technology.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] Examples include helicopter-airship hybrids intended for heavy-lift applications and dynamic-lift airships intended for long-range cruising.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] Most airships, when fully loaded with cargo and fuel, are ballasted to be heavier than air and thus must rely on their propulsion system and shape to generate the aerodynamic lift needed to stay aloft.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] All airships can be operated to be slightly heavier than air at periods during flight (descent).
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] Accordingly, the term "hybrid airship" refers to a craft that obtains a significant portion of its lift from aerodynamic lift or other kinetic means.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] For example, the Aeroscraft is a buoyancy-assisted air vehicle that generates lift through a combination of aerodynamics, thrust vectoring, and gas buoyancy generation and management, and will, for much of the time, fly heavier-than-air.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] Aeroscraft is Worldwide Aeros Corporation's continuation of DARPA's now cancelled Walrus HULA (Hybrid Ultra Large Aircraft) project.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] The Patroller P3 hybrid airship developed by Advanced Hybrid Aircraft Ltd, BC, Canada, is a relatively small (85,000 ft3 / 2,400 m3) buoyant craft, manned by the crew of five and with the endurance of up to 72 hours.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] The flight tests with the 40% RC scale model proved that such a craft can be launched and landed without a large team of strong ground-handlers.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] Design features a special "winglet" for aerodynamic lift control.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] Airships have been proposed as a potential, cheap alternative to surface rocket launches for achieving Earth orbit.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] JP Aerospace have proposed the Airship to Orbit project, which intends to float a multi-stage airship up to mesospheric altitudes of 55 km (180,000 ft) and then use ion propulsion to accelerate to orbital speed.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] At these heights, air resistance would not be a significant problem for achieving such speeds.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] The company has not yet built any of the three stages.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] NASA has proposed the High Altitude Venus Operational Concept, which comprises a series of five missions including crewed missions to the atmosphere of Venus in airships.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] Pressures on the surface of the planet are too high for human habitation, but at a specific altitude the pressure is equal to that found on Earth and this makes Venus a potential target for human colonization.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] Hypothetically, there could be an airship lifted by a vacuum—that is, by material that can contain nothing at all inside but withstand the atmospheric pressure from the outside.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] It is, at this point, science fiction, although NASA has posited that a vacuum airship could eventually be used to explore the surface of Mars.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] EU FP7 MAAT Project has studied an innovative cruiser/feeder airship system, for the stratosphere with a cruiser remaining airborne for a long time and feeders connecting it to the ground and flying as piloted balloons.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] Google co-founder Sergey Brin founded LTA Research in 2015 to develop airships for humanitarian and cargo transport.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] The company's 124-meter-long airship Pathfinder 1 received a special airworthiness certificate from the FAA for the helium-filled airship in September 2023.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] The certificate allowed the largest airship since the ill-fated Hindenburg to begin flight tests at Moffett Field, a joint civil-military airport in Silicon Valley.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] The Pathfinder is deemed the largest flying aircraft in size, beating that of the Stratolaunch Roc and many more.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] The advantage of airships over aeroplanes is that static lift sufficient for flight is generated by the lifting gas and requires no engine power.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] This was an immense advantage before the middle of World War I and remained an advantage for long-distance or long-duration operations until World War II.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] Modern concepts for high-altitude airships include photovoltaic cells to reduce the need to land for refueling, allowing them to remain airborne until their consumables expire.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] This similarly reduces or eliminates the need to consider variable fuel weight in buoyancy calculations.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] The disadvantages are that an airship has a very large reference area and a comparatively large drag coefficient, resulting in a larger drag force than aeroplanes and even helicopters.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] Given the large frontal area and wetted surface of an airship, a practical limit is reached around 130–160 kilometres per hour (80–100 mph), only about one-third the typical airspeed of a modern commercial airplane.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] Thus, airships are used where speed is not critical.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] The lift capability of an airship is equal to the buoyant force minus the weight of the airship.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] This assumes standard air-temperature and pressure conditions.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] Corrections are usually made for water vapor and impurities in the lifting gas, as well as for the gas-cell inflation percentage at liftoff.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] Based on specific lift (lifting force per unit volume of gas), the greatest static lift is provided by hydrogen (11.15 N/m3 or 71 lbf/1000 cu ft) with helium (10.37 N/m3 or 66 lbf/1000 cu ft) a close second.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] In addition to static lift, an airship can obtain a certain amount of dynamic lift from its engines.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] Dynamic lift in past airships has been about 10% of the static lift.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] Dynamic lift allows an airship to "take off heavy" from a runway similar to fixed-wing and rotary-wing aircraft.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] This requires additional weight in the engines, fuel, and landing gear, thereby reducing some of the static lift capacity.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] The altitude at which an airship can fly largely depends on how much lifting gas it can lose due to expansion before stasis is reached.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] The ultimate altitude record for a rigid airship was set in 1917 by the L-55 under the command of Hans-Kurt Flemming when he forced the airship to 7,300 m (24,000 ft) attempting to cross France after the "Silent Raid" on London.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] The L-55 lost lift during descent to lower altitudes over Germany and crashed.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] While such waste of gas was necessary for the survival of airships in the later years of World War I, it was impractical for commercial operations or operations of helium-filled military airships.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] The highest flight made by a hydrogen-filled passenger airship was 1,700 m (5,500 ft) on the *Graf Zeppelin's* around-the-world flight.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] The greatest disadvantage of the airship is size, which is essential to increasing performance.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] As size increases, the problems of ground handling increase geometrically.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] So long as the power-to-weight ratios of aircraft engines remained low and specific fuel consumption high, the airship had an edge for long-range or long-duration operations.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] As those figures changed, the balance shifted rapidly in the aeroplane's favour.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] By mid-1917, the airship could no longer survive in combat against aeroplanes.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] By the late 1930s, the airship barely had an advantage over the aeroplane on intercontinental over-water flights, and that advantage had vanished by the end of World War II.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] This is in face-to-face tactical situations.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] Currently, a high-altitude airship project is planned to survey hundreds of kilometres as their operation radius, often much farther than the normal engagement range of a military aeroplane.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] For example, a radar mounted on a vessel platform 30 m (100 ft) high has radio horizon at 20 km (12 mi) range, while a radar at 18,000 m (59,000 ft) altitude has radio horizon at 480 km (300 mi) range.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] This is significantly important for detecting low-flying cruise missiles or fighter-bombers.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] The most commonly used lifting gas, helium, is inert and therefore presents no fire risk.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] A series of vulnerability tests was done by the UK Defence Evaluation and Research Agency DERA on a Skyship 600.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] Since the internal gas pressure was maintained at only 1–2% above the surrounding air pressure, the vehicle proved highly tolerant to physical damage or to attack by small-arms fire or missiles.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] Several hundred high-velocity bullets were fired through the hull, and even two hours later, the vehicle would have been able to return to base.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] Ordnance passed through the envelope without causing critical helium loss.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] The results and related mathematical model are presented in the hypothesis of considering a Zeppelin NT-size airship.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] In all instances of light armament fire evaluated under both test and live conditions, the airship was able to complete its mission and return to base.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] In the United Kingdom, the basic pilot licence for airships is the PPL(As), or private pilot licence, which requires a minimum of 35 hours of instruction in airships.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/airship-p03] To fly commercially, a Commercial Pilot Licence (Airships) is required.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] The **armored cruiser** was a type of warship of the late 19th and early 20th centuries.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] It was designed like other types of cruisers to operate as a long-range, independent warship, capable of defeating any ship apart from a pre-dreadnought battleship and fast enough to outrun any battleship it encountered.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] For many decades, naval technology had not advanced far enough for designers to produce a cruiser that combined an armored belt with the long-range and high speed required to fulfill its mission.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] For this reason, beginning in the 1880s and 1890s, many navies preferred to build protected cruisers, which only relied on a lightly armored deck to protect the vital parts of the ship.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] However, by the late 1880s, the development of modern rapid-fire breech-loading cannons and high-explosive shells made the reintroduction of side armor a necessity.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] The invention of case-hardened armor in the mid-1890s offered effective protection with less weight than previously.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] Varying in size, the armored cruiser was distinguished from other types of cruiser by its belt armor—thick iron (or later steel) plating on much of the hull to protect the ship from shellfire much like that on battleships.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] The first armored cruiser, the Imperial Russian Navy's *General-Admiral*, was launched in 1873 and combined sail and steam propulsion.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] By the 1890s, cruisers had abandoned sail and took on a modern appearance.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] In 1908, the armored cruiser was supplanted by the battlecruiser, which, with armament equivalent to that of a dreadnought battleship and speed equivalent to that of a cruiser, was faster and more powerful than an armored cruiser.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] At around the same time there was a successor to the protected cruiser, the "light cruiser" which described small cruisers with armored belts.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] Although they were now considered second-rate ships, armored cruisers were still widely used in World War I due to their speed and range, and being able to outgun all but battlecruisers and battleships (both pre-dreadnought and dreadnought types).
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] A handful survived in one form or another until World War II.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] Only one, the Greek Navy's *Georgios Averof*, has survived to the modern day as a museum ship.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] The armored cruiser was developed in the 1870s as an attempt to combine the virtues of the armored ironclad warship and the fast and long-ranged, but unarmored, cruisers of the time.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] Such a ship was desirable to protect overseas trade and, especially for the French and British, to police their vast overseas empires.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] The concern within higher naval circles was that without ships that could fulfill these requirements and incorporate new technology, their fleet would become obsolete and ineffective should a war at sea arise.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] Concern over obsolescence in official circles was further fueled by the race between the increasing size of naval guns and of armor strong enough to withstand such fire.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] In 1860, one of the largest naval cannons in standard use had a bore of 8 inches (203 mm) and fired a 68-pound (31 kg) solid shot or approximately 51-pound (23 kg) spherical shell.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] By 1884, guns with as wide a bore as 16.25 inches (413 mm), firing an 1,800-pound (816 kg) exploding shell, were being mounted on naval vessels.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] This gun could penetrate up to 34 inches of wrought iron, the earliest form of naval armor.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] These were muzzle-loading guns, as had been used on ships from the 1500s.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] Breech-loading cannon, which were readopted into naval use in the 1870s, were more destructive than muzzle loaders due to their higher rate of fire.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] The development of rifled cannon, which improved accuracy, and advancements in shells were other factors.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] Although a cruiser would not likely face the largest-caliber guns of a battleship and many navies commonly used smaller weapons as they did not wear out as fast as larger ones did, cruisers still needed some form of protection to preclude being shot to pieces.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] The adoption of rolled iron armor in 1865 and sandwich armor in 1870 gave ships a chance to withstand fire from larger guns.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] Both these protective schemes used wood as an important component, which made them extremely heavy and limited speed, the key factor in a cruiser's ability to perform its duties satisfactorily.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] Powered by both sail and steam but without the additional weight of armor, these ships could reach speeds of up to 16 or 17 knots.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] The most powerful among them were the British *Inconstant*, the U.S.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] Navy's *Wampanoag* and the French *Duquesne*.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] The British especially had hoped to rely on these vessels to serve the more distant reaches of its empire.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] In the aftermath of the Battle of Hampton Roads in 1862, where United States wooden warships were defeated by the Confederate ironclad CSS *Virginia*, the Admiralty realized that its ships could theoretically encounter an ironclad in any theater of operation.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] Ship propulsion was improving but was also taking time to develop.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] Naval engines in the 1860s were single-expansion types, in which steam was expanded into a cylinder, pushed a piston and was released.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] Compounding, where steam is passed through a series of cylinders of increasing size before being released, was a more efficient process; it allowed the steam to generate more energy and use less coal to go the same distance.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] With greater efficiency came increasingly complex machinery and the larger potential for breakdown.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] However, advances in metallurgy and engineering, the potential for smaller bunkerage and the successful use of compounding in commercial engines made it an attractive option for naval engines, as well.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] By the 1870s, compound engines had become standard for warships.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] Compounding by itself did not increase power or speed significantly, although it allowed for a much greater operating range.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] Forced-draught systems would help increase power and speed but would not come into use until the early 1890s.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] The Russian navy became the first to produce an armored warship intended for commerce raiding, with *General-Admiral*, begun in 1870 and launched in 1873, often referred to as the first armored cruiser.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] Armed with six 8-inch (203 mm) and two 6-inch (152 mm) guns, she and her sister *Gerzog Edinburgski* were not fully armored but protected only by a narrow belt along the waterline.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] This belt, moreover, was so heavy that it sat below the ships' waterlines, which limited its benefit still further.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] Since they were iron-hulled, however, they were more durable than their wooden counterparts.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] With a top speed of only 12.3 knots (22.8 km/h) and a high coal consumption, which necessitated a full sailing rig, they were not really suited for the role of cruiser.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] Nevertheless, these ships were considered a new threat to British commerce in the event of war, the rationale being that any vessel, regardless of its speed, could technically be a threat to overseas commerce.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] The British responded with *Shannon*, begun in 1873, launched in 1875 and armed with two 10-inch (254 mm) and seven 9-inch (229 mm) rifled guns.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] Two ships of the *Nelson* class followed, armed with four 10-inch and eight 9-inch guns.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] These early armored cruisers were essentially scaled-down versions of the first-rate ironclad warships of the time and, like their Russian counterparts, were essentially belted cruisers.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] Their 9-inch belts were thicker than that of the Russians but did not extend the full length of the hull due to weight but tapered off at both ends.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] Past this belt, the designers placed a 3-inch (76 mm) armored deck, situated deepest in the ships, to guard magazines and machinery against plunging fire.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] Above this deck, space was allocated for coal bunkers and storerooms.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] The bunkers served as added protection, since two feet of coal was considered the equivalent of one foot of steel.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] Also, if either of the ships became flooded from battle damage, it was hoped the contents of the bunkers and storerooms would aid in their continued buoyancy.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] Because of this unarmored protection, these ships could be considered the first protected cruisers.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] However, these ships also shared the liabilities of the Russian ones and because of this, the British Navy was never happy with them.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] *Shannon*'s top speed of 12.25 knots (22.69 km/h) and *Nelson*'s of 14 knots (26 km/h) made them too slow to deal with fast cruisers and they were not armored well enough to take on a first-class battleship.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] Their armor belts also sat below the ships' waterlines, which made them of limited benefit.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] The underlying problem with these early warships was that technology had not caught up to the demands being made of them; therefore, they represented a series of compromises and could not be fully effective.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] They were typically powered by double-expansion steam engines fed by boilers which generated steam at perhaps 60 or 70 psi pressure, which gave relatively poor efficiency and short range.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] Even with improved engines, the dearth of overseas refueling stations made a full sailing rig a necessity.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] (The loss of HMS *Captain* in 1870 with nearly all of her 500-man crew illustrated graphically what could happen in a heavy sea with a steam-and-sail turret ship.) Consequently, armored cruisers retained a more traditional broadside arrangement.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] Their armor was distributed in a thick belt around the waterline along most of their length; the gun positions on deck were not necessarily armored at all.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] The limitations of these ships would not be rectified fully until decades after their construction.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] Meanwhile, a battle in May 1877 between the British unarmored cruiser *Shah* and the Peruvian monitor *Huáscar* demonstrated the need for more and better-protected cruisers.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] *Shah* and the smaller wooden corvette *Amethyst* hit *Huáscar* more than 50 times without causing significant damage.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] The Peruvian ship had an inexperienced crew unused to its cumbersome machinery, and managed to fire only six rounds, all of which missed.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] The engagement demonstrated the value of cruisers with armor protection.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] During the 1870s, the rapid increase in the size and power of armor-piercing guns caused problems for the designers of battleships and cruisers alike.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] Even a ship designed with adequate armor protection from the current generation of guns might be vulnerable to new guns powerful enough to penetrate its armor.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] Consequently, naval designers tried a novel method of armoring their ships.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] The vital parts—engines, boilers, magazines and enough hull structure to keep the ship stable in the event of damage—could be positioned underneath an armored deck just below the waterline.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] This deck, which would only be struck very obliquely by shells, could be thinner and lighter than belt armor.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] The sides of the ship would be entirely unarmored but would be as effective as an armored belt which would not stop shellfire.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] Cruisers designed along these guidelines, known as protected cruisers, superseded armored cruisers in the 1880s and early 1890s.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] As mentioned earlier, the armored cruiser *Shannon* was the first ship to make use of an armored deck.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] However, by the end of the 1870s, ships could be found with full–length armored decks and little or no side armor.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] The Italian *Italia* class of very fast battleships had armored decks and guns but no side armor.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] The British used a full-length armored deck in their *Comus* class of corvettes started in 1878; however the *Comus* class were designed for colonial service and were only capable of 13 knots (24 km/h) speed, not fast enough for commerce protection or fleet duties.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] The breakthrough for the protected cruiser design came with the Chilean *Esmeralda*, designed and built by the British firm Armstrong at their Elswick yard.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] *Esmeralda*, with a high speed of 18 knots (33 km/h), dispensed entirely with sails and carried an armament of two 10-inch and six 6-inch guns, considered very powerful for a ship her size.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] Her protection scheme, inspired by the *Italia* class, included a full–length protected deck up to 2 inches (51 mm) thick, and a cork-filled cofferdam along her sides.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] *Esmeralda* set the tone for cruiser construction for the years to come, with "Elswick cruisers" on a similar design being constructed for Italy, China, Japan, Argentina, Austria and the United States.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] Protected cruisers became attractive for two reasons.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] First, the concept of the armored cruiser was not embraced wholeheartedly in naval circles.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] Second, several navies were caught in a race between armor thickness and the size of main guns and did not have the money to spend on battleships and armored cruisers.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] The use of smaller, cheaper cruisers was a better alternative.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] The French navy adopted the protected cruiser wholeheartedly in the 1880s.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] The *Jeune Ecole* school of thought, which proposed a navy composed of fast cruisers for commerce raiding and torpedo-boats for coast defense, was particularly influential in France.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] The first French protected cruiser was *Sfax*, laid down in 1882, and followed by six classes of protected cruiser – and no armored cruisers until *Dupuy de Lôme*, laid down in 1888 but not finished until 1895.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] *Dupuy de Lôme* was a revolutionary ship, being the first French armored cruiser to dispose entirely of masts, and sheathed in steel armor.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] However, she and two others were not sufficiently seaworthy, and their armor could be penetrated by modern quick-firing guns.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] Thus from 1891 to 1897 the French reverted to the construction of protected cruisers.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] The British Royal Navy was equivocal about which protection scheme to use until 1887.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] The large *Imperieuse* class, begun in 1881 and finished in 1886, were built as armored cruisers but were often referred to as protected cruisers.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] While they carried an armored belt some 10 in thick, the belt only covered 140 ft (43 m) of the 315 ft (96 m) length of the ship, and was submerged below the waterline at full load.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] The real protection of the class came from the armored deck 4 in (102 mm) thick, and the arrangement of coal bunkers to prevent flooding.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] These ships were also the last armored cruisers to be designed with sails.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] However, on trials it became clear that the masts and sails did more harm than good; they were removed and replaced by a single military mast with machine guns.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] The next class of small cruisers in the Royal Navy, the *Mersey* class, were protected cruisers, but the Royal Navy then returned to the armored cruiser with the *Orlando* class, begun in 1885 and completed in 1889.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] The navy judged the *Orlando*s inferior to protected cruisers and built exclusively protected cruisers immediately afterwards, including some very large, fast ships like the 14,000-ton *Powerful* class.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] However, the *Orlando*s were the first class of cruiser to use the triple-expansion engine.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] Because this type of reciprocating engine used the steam in three stages, it was more fuel-efficient than earlier compound engines.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] It also used steam of higher pressure, 60 poundforce per square inch, as compared to the 25 to 30 poundforce in earlier engines.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] With these engineering developments, warships could now dispense with sails and be entirely steam-driven.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] The only major naval power to retain a preference for armored cruisers during the 1880s was Russia.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] The Russian Navy laid down four armored cruisers and one protected cruiser during the decade, all being large ships with sails.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] The development of rapid–fire cannons in the late 1880s forced a change in cruiser design.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] Since a large number of hits at or near the waterline could negate the effect of water–excluding material used in protected cruisers, side armor again became a priority.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] However, it had to cover not just guns and the waterline but also much of the hull structure in–between; otherwise, the equally new high–explosive shells could penetrate and destroy much of the unarmored portion of the ship.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] Another development was the publication in 1890 of American naval strategist Alfred Thayer Mahan's book *The Influence of Sea Power upon History*.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] The armored cruisers built in the mid– to late–1890s were often as large and expensive as pre-dreadnought battleships.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] They combined long range, high speed and an armament approaching that of battleship with enough armor to protect them against quick-firing guns, considered the most important weapons afloat at the time.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] Their speed was made possible due to another development, case-hardened steel armor—first Harvey armor and then crucially Krupp armor.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] The higher tensile strength of these armors compared to nickel steel and mild steel made it feasible to put a light yet useful armor belt on a large cruiser.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] They saved further weight by not requiring a heavy timber backing, as previous armor plating had, to soften and spread the force of the impact from oncoming shells; 2.5 inches (64 mm) of teak to give a fair surface upon which to attach them was all that was needed.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] Moreover, this belt could also be much wider than previously, covering the center of the hull, where the ammunition and engines were located, from the main deck to five feet below the waterline.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] Steel bulkheads added strength to the hull, while armor as thick as the belt covered the guns and heavier protection surrounded the conning tower.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] With these improvements, the ships became more fully protected than was possible previously.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] They were also expensive to maintain at fighting strength as they required a greater number of stokers to feed the boilers than a battleship when steaming at flank speed.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] The ideas presented by Mahan prompted French Admiral Ernest François Fournier to write his book *La flotte necessaire* in 1896.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] Fournier argued that a fleet of technologically advanced armored cruisers and torpedo craft would be powerful and flexible enough to engage in a wide range of activity and overwhelm potential enemies.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] French naval and government circles embraced this ideal mutually and even advocates of battleships over cruisers admitted the latter's potential usefulness in scouting and commercial warfare.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] The result was the building of increasingly large armored cruisers.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] *Jeanne d'Arc*, laid down in 1896, displaced 11,000 tons, carried a mixed armament of 194-millimetre (7.6 in) and 138-millimetre (5.4 in) guns, and had a 150-millimetre (5.9 in) belt of Harvey armor over her machinery spaces.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] The 12,300-ton *Léon Gambetta* class and 14,000-ton *Edgar Quinet* class followed.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] The *Edgar Quinet*s, slightly faster at 23 knots, were armed with 14 194-millimetre (7.6 in) guns and carried up to 170-millimetre (6.7 in) of armor on their belts, almost 100-millimetre (3.9 in) on their decks and 150-millimetre (5.9 in) on their turrets.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] At 21 knots, the *Cressy*s were slower than the newer French cruisers.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] However, their 6-inch (152 mm) belt of Krupp steel was expected to keep out armor-piercing shells from a 6-inch (152 mm) quick-firing gun at likely battle ranges, while their two 9.2-inch (233.7 mm) and 12 6-inch (152 mm) guns offered comparable firepower.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] The 2,500-ton weight of their belt armor was an improvement over the 1809 tons of the otherwise similar *Diadem* class and very similar to that of the *Canopus* class of battleships.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] The *Cressy*s were the beginning of a rapid expansion in British cruiser construction.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] Between 1899 and 1905, seven classes of armored cruisers were either completed or laid down, a total of 35 ships.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] Japan, which now received British technical assistance in naval matters and purchased larger vessels from France and Britain, began an armored cruiser program of its own.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] The core of this 109-ship build-up was the "Six-Six Program" of six battleships and six (eventually eight) armored cruisers comparable to the British *Cressy* class.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] They were considered a compromise between cruiser and battleship and were intended to augment capital ship strength in battle squadrons.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] This practice would persist until World War I.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] The first United States armored cruiser, USS *Maine*, was launched in 1889 but not completed until 1895 due to a three-year delay in the delivery of her armor plate.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] However, *Maine* was laid down before Harvey or Krupp armor was available and could not benefit from the advantage in weight these much lighter armors offered.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] She was redesignated a "second-class battleship" in 1894, an awkward compromise reflecting that, at 16.45 knots, she was considerably slower than other cruisers and weaker than first-line battleships.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] Her destruction in Havana harbor in 1898 was a catalyst in starting the Spanish–American War.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] Shortly after the war ended, the Navy laid down six *Pennsylvania*-class armored cruisers to take advantage of lessons learned and better control the large sea areas the nation had just gained.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] Much larger than their predecessors (displacing 14,500 tons as compared to 8150 for *New York*), the *Pennsylvania*s "were closer to light battleships than to cruisers," according to naval historian William Friedman.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] They carried four 8-inch (203 mm) and 14 6-inch (152 mm) guns, 6 inches (152 mm) of armor on their belts, 6.5 inches (165 mm) on their turrets and 9 inches (229 mm) on their conning towers.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] Their deck armor was light at 1.5 inches (38 mm) for flat surfaces and 3 inches (76 mm) for sloped, a compromise made for faster speed (22 knots, compared with 20 knots for *Brooklyn*).
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] Improved ammunition made their main guns as powerful as the 12-inch (305 mm) guns of the battleship *Iowa* and their use of state instead of city names, usually reserved for capital ships, emphasized their kinship.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] More often, they were seen fighting in a battle line.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] They would not been seen in their designed role until World War I.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] Even with all their improvements and apparent performance, opinion on the armored cruiser was mixed.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] Navy in hearings before the House of Representatives gave testimony to the effect that no armored cruisers were further planned nor to it knowledge were armored cruisers being built by any major naval power worldwide.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] Armored cruisers were used with success in the line of battle by the Japanese at the Battle of Tsushima in 1905.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] Of the battle damage received by the Japanese, the armored cruiser *Nisshin* received eight hits, which destroyed three of her 8-inch (203 mm) guns, killed five crew members and injured 90 more (one of the wounded being Isoroku Yamamoto, who would later plan the attack on Pearl Harbor).
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] None of the other Japanese armored cruisers suffered serious damage or large loss of life.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] *Iwate* was hit 16 times but no one onboard was killed and only 15 were wounded.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] Except for *Kasagi*, all the cruisers present at Tsushima that morning were still battle-ready in the evening.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] Danish Navy Commander William Hovgaard, who would later become president of New York Shipbuilding and serve on the U.S.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] Buoyed with their success at Tsushima, Japan laid down the four *Tsukuba*-class cruisers between 1905 and 1908.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] At a speed of 20.5 knots, they carried an extremely heavy main armament of four 12-inch (305 mm) guns, 8 inches (203 mm) of belt and turret armor and 3 inches (76 mm) of deck armor.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] The *Tsukuba*s were intended to take the place of aging battleships and thus showed Japan's intention of continuing to use armored cruisers in fleet engagements.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] Navy raised the main gun caliber of its cruisers with its *Tennessee* class, laid down between 1902 and 1904.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] These mounted four 10-inch (254 mm) and 16 6-inch (152 mm) guns, the former a size previously allocated to battleships.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] While they had thinner armor than the *Pennsylvania*s (5 inches (127 mm) on their belts and 1 inch (25 mm) on their decks) due to newly imposed congressional restraints on tonnage, they could still steam at 22 knots.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] They were built as a fast, powerful response in the eventuality of a Pacific war and were the largest and last American armored cruisers built.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] The British also considered 10-inch (254 mm) and 12-inch (305 mm) guns for its *Minotaur*-class cruisers, the culmination of its armored cruiser building program.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] They displaced 14,600 tons, were capable of 23 knots and were armed with four 9.2-inch (234 mm) and 10 7.5-inch (191 mm) guns.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] By the time these ships were commissioned, Britain possessed the largest armored cruiser force in the world.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] Undaunted and fully engaged in a naval arms race with the British, the Germans also continued to build armored cruisers, partly from their faith in them as fighting units and commerce raiders, partly from Japan's success.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] Between 1897 and 1906 they laid down eight of them for use on overseas stations.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] The initial two, SMS *Fürst Bismarck* and SMS *Prinz Heinrich*, were armed with 9.44-inch (240 mm) guns; the six that followed had 8.2-inch (208 mm) guns of a more modern design.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] The final pair, *Scharnhorst* and *Gneisenau*, displaced 12,781 tons, steamed at 23.5 knots, carried 6 inches (152 mm) of belt and 2 inches (51 mm) of deck armor and were armed with eight 8.2-inch (208 mm) guns.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] Another powerful armored cruiser was the Russian *Rurik*, completed in 1908.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] Armed with four 10-inch (254 mm) in two twin turrets fore and aft and eight 8-inch (203 mm) in turrets along the ship's sides, she displaced 15,190 tons and carried a 6-inch (152 mm) belt, two armored decks and 8-inch (203 mm) armor on her turrets and conning tower.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] *Rurik* was unusual in that she was Russian designed but British built; the Russian Navy was not usually a customer of British shipyards.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] She was reportedly one of the best armored cruisers built, with an advanced sprinkler protection for the magazines.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] Intended as the first of a three-ship class, *Rurik*'s sisters were cancelled with the advent of the battlecruiser HMS *Invincible*.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] "The supreme embodiment of the armored cruiser," in historian Robert K.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] Massie's words, was the German ship SMS *Blücher*.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] An enlarged version of the *Scharnhorst* class with a speed of 24.25 knots, armed with 12 8.2-inch (208 mm) and eight 5.9-inch (150 mm) guns, *Blücher* was planned as an armored cruiser in part because the British had misled the Germans on the *Invincible*s then being constructed.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] The Germans expected these new British ships to be armed with six or eight 9.2 in (23 cm) guns.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] One week after the final decision to construct *Blücher*, the German naval attache learned they would carry eight 30.5 cm (12.0 in) guns, the same type mounted on battleships.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] With no funds available to redesign *Blücher*, work was ordered to proceed as scheduled.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] Although much more powerful than a typical armored cruiser, she was significantly weaker than the new British battlecruisers.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] By the time these new armored cruisers were entering service, such types of ships had reached the end of its development.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] Thirty percent was the ratio by which frigates had been faster than ships of the line in the days of sail.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] If a battleship sailed at 20 knots, this would mean that an armored cruiser would have to steam at least 26 or 27 knots.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] To fulfill these criteria, however, armored cruisers would have to be built much larger and take on a different form than they had in the past.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] First Sea Lord "Jacky" Fisher, an advocate of armored cruisers as more useful than battleships to safeguard British trade and territorial interests, saw his efforts justified; his belief that "speed is armor" would lead him to create the battlecruiser.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] The battlecruiser HMS *Invincible* and her two sister ships were designed specifically to fulfill these requirements.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] Because they carried the heavy guns normally ascribed to battleships, they could also theoretically hold their place in a battle line more readily than armored cruisers and serve as the "battleship-cruiser" for which Hovgaard had argued after Tsushima.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] All these factors made battlecruisers attractive fighting units, although Britain, Germany and Japan would be the only powers to build them.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] They also meant that the armored cruiser as it had been known was now outmoded and no more were built after 1910.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] Later in the same address is this: "Every argument used against [armored cruisers] holds true for battle-cruisers of the *Invincible* type, except that the latter, if wounded, would be fit to lie in the line, owing to her great armament.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] Although pre-dreadnought battleships and armored cruisers were outclassed by modern battleship and battlecruiser designs, respectively, armored cruisers still played an active role in World War I.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] Their armor and firepower was sufficient to defeat other cruiser types and armed merchant vessels, while their speed and range made them particularly useful for extended operations out in the high seas.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] Some German and Royal Navy vessels, like HMS *Good Hope*, were allocated to remote naval squadrons.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] Many other vessels however, were formed into independent squadrons for patrolling European waters and accompanied capital ships every time the latter made forays out of port.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] At the Battle of Coronel, the German armored cruisers SMS *Scharnhorst* and SMS *Gneisenau* scored a resounding victory over British naval forces from the West Indies Station.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] With newer ships, superior gunnery and optimal logistics, the Germans sank the Royal Navy armored cruisers HMS *Monmouth* and HMS *Good Hope*, with the loss of over 1,500 British sailors and officers (including Rear-Admiral Christopher Cradock).
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] This was one of the last battles involving armored cruisers as the chief adversaries; all subsequent engagements were dominated by battlecruisers and dreadnought battleships.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] Moreover, the timing could not have been worse for British morale.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] Six weeks earlier, the armored cruisers HMS *Cressy*, HMS *Hogue* and HMS *Aboukir* had all been sunk on the same day by the German submarine U-9.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] Five weeks later, the Battle of the Falkland Islands showed graphically how much technology and tactics had changed.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] SMS *Scharnhorst* and SMS *Gneisenau* were sunk by a British force of the battlecruisers HMS *Invincible* and HMS *Inflexible*, three armoured cruisers and two light cruisers.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] The German armored cruisers were too slow to outrun their pursuers, and their initially accurate gunnery failed to inflict serious damage on the British battlecruisers.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] The British 12-inch guns turned the tide of battle once they started scoring hits on the Germans, and the German armored cruisers were fatally crippled before they had a chance to close the range and use their superior secondary armament.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] This victory seemed to validate Lord "Jacky" Fisher's justification in building battlecruisers—to track down and destroy armored cruisers with vessels possessing superior speed and firepower.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] The German force commander Admiral Maximilian von Spee had been wary of the Allies' battlecruisers, especially the Imperial Japanese Navy and the Royal Australian Navy—in fact he described the latter's flagship, the battlecruiser HMAS *Australia*, as being superior to his entire force by itself.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] At the Falklands, he had already deduced the battle was lost when he missed the chance to attack the British battlecruisers in port.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] During the Battle of Dogger Bank, *Blücher* was crippled by a shell from a British battlecruiser, which slowed *Blücher* to 17 knots and eventually sealed her fate.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] Admiral Franz von Hipper chose to let *Blücher* go down so his more valuable battlecruisers could escape.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] HMS *Warrior*, HMS *Defence* and HMS *Black Prince* were lost at the Battle of Jutland when they inadvertently came into sight and range of the German Navy's battle line, which included several battlecruisers and dreadnought battleships.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] The armor belt was shown to be far less than required to survive the 280mm (11 inch) and 300 mm (12 inch) shells of more modern dreadnoughts and battlecruisers and the cruisers were too slow to get away from them.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] The final nail in the coffin for the armored cruiser type was in the development of capped armor-piercing shells.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] The Harvey and Krupp Cemented armor that had looked to offer protection failed when hit with soft capped AP shells of large enough size.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] Later hard capped AP shell would only make the matter worse.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] After the end of World War I, many of the surviving armored cruisers were sold for scrap.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] The Washington Naval Treaty of 1922 placed strict limits on the numbers of "capital ships" possessed by the navies of the great powers.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] A "capital ship" was defined as any vessel of over 10,000 tons displacement or with guns over 8-in caliber, and several more armored cruisers were decommissioned to comply with the terms of the treaty.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] The London Naval Treaty of 1930 introduced further limits on cruiser tonnage, and the former role of the armored cruiser was occupied by more modern light cruisers and heavy cruisers (and, in the case of the German navy, panzerschiffe).
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] The Hellenic Navy's *Georgios Averof*, constructed in 1909, served with the British Navy as a convoy escort in the Indian Ocean after the fall of Greece, while a number of Japanese armored cruisers were still active as minelayers or training vessels.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] The Imperial Japanese Navy armored cruisers *Asama*, *Izumo*, *Tokiwa*, *Iwate*, *Yakumo*, *Azuma*, & *Kasuga* were used as training, support, and anti-aircraft ships during the war near the Japanese home islands.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] Most were sunk by Allied bombings in Japanese harbors.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] The Regia Marina's *San Giorgio* was deployed to Spain to protected Italian interests during the Spanish Civil War.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] During World War II, she was heavily utilized at the Siege of Tobruk.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] There she provided anti-aircraft cover and naval gunfire support to Italian units.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] She was heavily damaged by British aircraft and was scuttled to prevent her capture.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] Her sister ship, *San Marco* was decommissioned in 1931 and used as a radio controlled target ship.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] In 1943, she was scuttled to prevent her capture by the Germans.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] The United States Navy's USS *Rochester*, decommissioned since 1933, was moored in Subic Bay and used as a receiving ship and anti-aircraft platform.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] She was later scuttled to prevent her capture by the Japanese during the Invasion of The Philippines.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] The Argentine Navy's ARA *General Belgrano* and ARA *Pueyrredón* served until 1947 and 1954 respectfully.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] The Swedish Navy's HSwMS *Fylgia* underwent an extensive modernization from 1939 to 1940 and conducted neutrality patrols in the Baltic Sea during World War II.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] The only armored cruiser still considered to be in existence, as well as in active duty, is the aforementioned *Georgios Averof*, preserved as a museum in Palaio Faliro, Greece.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] The armored cruiser was not a close ancestor of heavy cruisers, even though the name might suggest this.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] The armored cruiser type had come about in a time of transition as one technology after another presented itself.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] Boilers had become better (though still in need of improvement), and Krupp cemented armor and compound steam engines had arrived.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] The rate of change was nothing less than staggering and any ship more than 20 years old was found to be completely obsolete.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] The Italian Navy, unable to afford battleships, produced the *Garibaldi*-class cruiser of 7,500 tons displacement which was an international success.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] White DNC of the British Royal Navy was taken by the design and presented the design for the *Cressy*-class cruiser of 12,000 tons displacement designed from the onset as an adjunct to the pre-dreadnought battle line, on 3 May 1897.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] As such the armored cruiser is the direct predecessor of and inspiration for the battlecruiser.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] There were also important technical differences between the heavy cruiser and the armored cruiser, some of which reflected the generational gap between them.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] Heavy cruisers were typically powered by oil-fired superheated steam boilers and steam turbine engines, and were capable of far faster speeds than armored cruisers (propelled by coal-fired reciprocating steam engines of their era) ever had been.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] Countries withdrawing from the Washington Treaty and the London Naval Treaty of 1930 and Second London Naval Treaty 1936 eventually rendered all limitations on heavy cruisers moot, although the only supersized or large cruisers actually built were the two members of the *Alaska* class.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] Armored cruisers were often pressed into the main line of battle against battlecruisers and dreadnought battleships (battles of the Falkland Islands, Dogger Bank and Jutland).
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/armoured-cruiser] By contrast, heavy cruisers and light cruisers were not expected to be deployed as such, although there had been some notable engagements (battles of the Denmark Strait, Matapan, Guadalcanal and Surigao Strait).
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/arthur-constantin-krebs] Collaborating with Charles Renard, Krebs piloted the first fully controlled free-flight made in the French Army airship *La France*, which was designed in 1884.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/arthur-constantin-krebs] The flight covered 8 km (5.0 mi) in 23 minutes.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/arthur-constantin-krebs] The flight landed back at its starting point.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/arthur-constantin-krebs] On its seven flights the *La France* dirigible returned five times to its starting point.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/arthur-constantin-krebs] Krebs and Renard shared the 1886 Ponti prize of the French *Académie des sciences* for their contribution to aerostation.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/arthur-constantin-krebs] In Verne's 1886 novel *Robur The Conqueror*, he writes of "the striking experiments of Captain Krebs and Captain Renard".
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/arthur-constantin-krebs] In 1888 Krebs and Gustave Zédé designed the first modern French submarine, the *Gymnote*.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/arthur-constantin-krebs] The submarine was fitted with the first naval periscope and the first naval electric gyrocompass.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/arthur-constantin-krebs] The latter allowed the *Gymnote* to force a naval block in 1890.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/arthur-constantin-krebs] From 1884 to 1897 Arthur Krebs modernized the *Ville de Paris* fire department; not only its equipment but its organisation as well.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/arthur-constantin-krebs] His work left a lasting impression in this elite corps.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/arthur-constantin-krebs] In May 1896 Arthur Krebs patented a new automobile, fitted with an electromagnetic gearbox and a layout of the front wheels which re-centred them when the steering wheel was left alone.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/arthur-constantin-krebs] Today this is known as the Castor angle.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/arthur-constantin-krebs] The Panhard et Levassor company acquired a license to build 500 cars under the name of Clement-Panhard between 1898 and 1902 featuring this innovation.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/arthur-constantin-krebs] Krebs succeeded Levassor as Panhard et Levassor's general manager from 1897 to 1916.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/arthur-constantin-krebs] He transformed the Panhard et Levassor Company into one of the largest and most profitable automobile manufacturers before World War I.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/arthur-constantin-krebs] In 1898 Krebs replaced the tiller with an inclined steering wheel for the Panhard et Levassor car he designed for the Paris-Amsterdam race which ran from 7 to 13 July 1898.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/arthur-constantin-krebs] Fernand Charron won that race on a four-cylinder Panhard et Levassor.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/arthur-constantin-krebs] At the end of 1898, C S Rolls introduced the first car in Britain fitted with wheel steering when he imported a 6 hp Panhard et Levassor from France.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/arthur-constantin-krebs] In 1902 Krebs invented the automatic diaphragm carburettor which gave cars continuous power during acceleration by providing a constant air-fuel ratio at all times; this also led to dramatic improvement in fuel economy.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/arthur-constantin-krebs] In 1906 Krebs traveled to the United States to plead in the Selden Case, associated with Henry Ford.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/arthur-constantin-krebs] Also, Krebs contributed significantly to improve the Systeme Panhard (engine in front, rear wheel drive) which became universally adopted before World War II.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/arthur-constantin-krebs] In 1909 Krebs became interested in the Knight patent (sleeve valve engine).
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/arthur-constantin-krebs] He was also the first person in France to build that type of engine which Panhard et Levassor would produce during the thirty years leading up to World War II.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/arthur-constantin-krebs] He made contributions to automotive racing with his powerful cars and motorboats.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/arthur-constantin-krebs] In 1911 Krebs invented the first elastomeric flexible coupling (cf.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/arthur-constantin-krebs] It is known in French as the *Flector* joint.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/arthur-constantin-krebs] This device is still widely used today in industry for power transmission as a *tyre coupling*.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/arthur-constantin-krebs] The truck was meant for military and civil purposes.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/arthur-constantin-krebs] In 1911, jointly with the Chatillon Co, Krebs designed the *Tracteur Chatillon-Panhard* all-terrain truck.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/arthur-constantin-krebs] The truck had four wheel drive and four wheel steering and many were used during World War I as artillery tractors.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/arthur-constantin-krebs] Krebs also utilized his former military membership to supply the French Army with engines and vehicles including the 1904 Genty Armored car, the 1916 St Chamond tank, the Chatillon-Panhard 4x4 truck, and others.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/arthur-constantin-krebs] In 1960, the United Kingdom Antarctic Place-Names Committee (UK-APC) named Krebs Glacier, a glacier flowing west into the head of Charlotte Bay on the west coast of Graham Land in the Antarctic continent, after Krebs.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/arthur-constantin-krebs] In 1934, several months before Arthur Krebs's death, he was made a Commandeur of the Legion of Honour for his work in Aeronautics and for his contributions to the automotive industry.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] A **battleship** is a large, heavily armored warship with a main battery consisting of large guns, designed to serve as a capital ship.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] From their advent in the late 1880s, battleships were among the largest and most formidable warship types ever built, until they were surpassed by aircraft carriers beginning in the 1940s.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] The modern battleship traces its origin to the sailing ship of the line, which was developed into the steam ship of the line and soon thereafter the ironclad warship.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] After a period of extensive experimentation in the 1870s and 1880s, ironclad design was largely standardized by the British *Royal Sovereign* class, which are usually referred to as the first "pre-dreadnought battleships".
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] These ships carried an armament that usually included four large guns and several medium-caliber guns that were to be used against enemy battleships, and numerous small guns for self-defense.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] Naval powers around the world built dozens of pre-dreadnoughts in the 1890s and early 1900s, though they saw relatively little combat; only two major wars were fought during the period that included pre-dreadnought battles: the Spanish–American War in 1898 and the Russo-Japanese War of 1904–1905.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] The following year, the British launched the revolutionary all-big-gun battleship HMS *Dreadnought*.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] This ship discarded the medium-caliber guns in exchange for a uniform armament of ten large guns.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] All other major navies quickly began (or had already started) "dreadnoughts" of their own, leading to a major naval arms race.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] During World War I, only one major fleet engagement took place: the Battle of Jutland in 1916, but neither side was able to achieve a decisive result.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] In the Interwar period, the major naval powers concluded a series of agreements beginning with the Washington Naval Treaty that imposed limits on battleship building to stop a renewed arms race.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] During this period, relatively few battleships were built, but advances in technology led to the maturation of the fast battleship concept, and several of these ships were built in the 1930s.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] The treaty system eventually broke down after Japan refused to sign the Second London Naval Treaty in 1936.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] Although the rise of the aircraft carrier during World War II largely relegated battleships to secondary duties, they still saw significant action during that conflict.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] Notable engagements include the battles of Cape Spartivento and Cape Matapan in 1940 and 1941, respectively; the sortie by the German battleship *Bismarck* in 1941; the Naval Battle of Guadalcanal in 1942; and the Battle of Leyte Gulf in 1944.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] After World War II, most battleships were placed in reserve, broken up, or used as target ships, and few saw significant active service during the Cold War.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] The four American *Iowa*-class battleships were reactivated during the Korean War in the early 1950s and again in the 1980s as part of the 600-ship Navy.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] Even at the height of their dominance of naval combat, some strategists questioned the usefulness of battleships.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] Beginning in the mid-1880s, the *Jeune École* (Young School) argued that construction of expensive capital ships should stop in favor of cheap cruisers and torpedo boats.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] Despite a period of popularity for the *Jeune École*, the idea fell out of favor and the battleship remained the arbiter of naval combat until World War II.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] Even afterward, they remained potent symbols of a country's might and they retained significant psychological and diplomatic effects.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] A number of battleships—predominantly American—remain as museum ships.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] A ship of the line was a large, unarmored wooden sailing ship which mounted a battery of up to 120 smoothbore guns and carronades, which came to prominence with the adoption of line of battle tactics in the early 17th century.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] From 1794, the alternative term 'line of battle ship' was contracted to 'battle ship' or 'battleship'.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] The sheer number of guns fired broadside meant a ship of the line could wreck any wooden enemy, holing her hull, knocking down masts, wrecking her rigging, and killing her crew.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] They also imparted a psychological effect on the crews of smaller vessels.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] Ships of the line were also fairly resilient to the guns of the day; for example, the British Royal Navy lost no first-rate (the largest type of ship of the line) to enemy action during the entire 18th century.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] Over time, ships of the line gradually became larger and carried more guns, but otherwise remained quite similar.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] Development of the first-rates was particularly conservative, as these ships represented a major investment.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] By the early 1800s, the traditional "seventy-four" (so-named because it carried 74 guns) was no longer considered to be a proper ship of the line, having been supplanted by 84- and 120-gun ships.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] The first major change to the ship of the line concept was the introduction of steam power as an auxiliary propulsion system.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] Steam power was gradually introduced to the navy in the first half of the 19th century, initially for small craft and later for frigates.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] Early vessels used paddle wheels for propulsion, but by the 1840s, the first screw propeller equipped vessels began to appear.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] The value of these smaller steam-powered warships demonstrated their worth, when vessels like the British *Nemesis* proved to be critical to the Anglo-French success in the First Opium War in the 1840s.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] The French Navy introduced steam to the line of battle with the 90-gun *Napoléon* in 1850—the first true steam battleship.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] *Napoléon*, which was designed by Henri Dupuy de Lôme, was armed as a conventional ship-of-the-line, but her steam engines could give her a speed of 12 knots (22 km/h; 14 mph), regardless of the wind.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] This was a potentially decisive advantage in a naval engagement.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] The introduction of steam accelerated the growth in size of battleships.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] France and the United Kingdom were the only countries to develop fleets of wooden, steam-screw battleships although several other navies operated small numbers of screw battleships, including Russia (9), the Ottoman Empire (3), Sweden (2), Naples (1), Denmark (1) and Austria (1).
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] Concurrent with the development of steam power, another major technological step heralded the end of the traditional ship of the line: guns capable of firing explosive shells.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] Pioneering work was done by the French artillery officer Henri-Joseph Paixhans beginning in 1809.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] The American artillerist George Bomford followed not far behind, designing the first shell-firing Columbiad in 1812.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] The British and Russians began to follow suit in the 1830s, though early smoothbore guns could not fire shells as far as solid shot, which hampered widespread adoption in any fleet.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] By the early 1840s, the French Paixhans gun and American Dahlgren gun had begun to be adopted by their respective navies.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] In the Crimean War of 1853–1855, six Russian ships of the line and two frigates of the Black Sea Fleet destroyed seven Turkish frigates and three corvettes with explosive shells at the Battle of Sinop in 1853.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] The battle was widely seen as vindication of the shell gun.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] Despite losing her bowsprit and her foremast, and being set on fire, she was ready for action again the very next day.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] As amply demonstrated at the Battle of Sinop, and again during the Anglo-French blockade of Sevastopol from 1854 to 1855, wooden ships had become vulnerable to shell-firing guns.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] This prompted the French emperor Napoleon III to order the first ironclad warships: the *Dévastation*-class ironclad floating batterys.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] Three of these ships led the Anglo-French attack on the Russian fortress on the Kinburn Peninsula in the Battle of Kinburn in 1855, where they bore the brunt of Russian artillery fire, but were not seriously damaged.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] The success of these ships prompted the French and British to order several similar vessels.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] In March 1858, the French took development of the ironclad to its next logical step: a proper, ocean-going armored warship.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] This vessel, another design by Dupuy de Lome, was *Gloire*, and after her launching in 1859, Napoleon III ordered another five similar ships, which sparked a naval arms race with Britain.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] The first French ironclads had the profile of a ship of the line, cut to one deck due to weight considerations.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] Although made of wood and reliant on sail for most journeys, *Gloire* and her contemporaries were fitted with screw propellers, and their wooden hulls were protected by a layer of thick iron armor.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] Britain responded promptly with *Warrior*, a similar but much larger ironclad with an iron hull.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] By the time *Warrior* was completed in 1861, another nine ironclads were under construction in British shipyards, some of which were conversions of screw ships of the line that were already being built.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] Spain and Russia ordered ironclads in 1861, as did the United States and rebel Confederate States of America after the start of the American Civil War.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] Construction of these large and expensive warships remained controversial until March 1862, when news of the Battle of Hampton Roads, fought between the Union USS *Monitor* and the Confederate CSS *Virginia*, firmly settled debate in favor of even larger construction programs.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] From the 1860s to 1880s, navies experimented with the positioning of guns, in turrets, central-batteries, or barbettes; ironclads of the period also prominently used the ram as a principal weapon.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] As steam technology developed, masts were gradually removed from battleship designs.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] The British Chief Constructor, Edward Reed, produced the *Devastation*-class ironclads in 1869.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] These were mastless turret ships, which adopted twin-screw propulsion and an arrangement of two pairs of 12-inch (305 mm) guns, one fore and one aft of the superstructure, that prefigured the advent of the pre-dreadnought battleship some two decades later.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] By the mid-1870s steel was used as a construction material alongside iron and wood.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] The French Navy's *Redoutable*, laid down in 1873 and launched in 1876, was a combination central battery and barbette ship, which became the first capital ship in the world to use steel as the principal building material.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] The rapid pace of technological developments, particularly in terms of gun capabilities and thickness of armor to combat them, quickly rendered ships obsolescent.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] In the continuous attempt by gun manufacturers to keep ahead of developments in armor plate, larger and larger guns were fitted to many of the later ironclads.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] Some of these, such as the British *Victoria* class, carried guns as large as 16.25 inches (413 mm) in diameter, while the Italian *Duilio*-class ironclads were armed with colossal 17.7-inch (450 mm) guns.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] In the 1880s, opposition to fleets of large, expensive ironclads arose around the world, but most notably in France, where a group of naval officers led by Admiral Théophile Aube formed the *Jeune École* (Young School).
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] The theory, which held as one of its core tenets that small, cheap torpedo boats could easily defeat ironclads, was based on combat experience during the Russo-Turkish War of 1877–1878.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] The doctrine also posited that modern steel-hulled cruisers could defeat a more powerful navy by attacking the country's merchant shipping, rather than engage in a direct battle.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] The concept proved to be highly influential for several years, shaping the construction programs of France, Germany, Italy, and Austria-Hungary, among others throughout the world.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] In 1889, the British government passed the Naval Defence Act 1889, which embarked on a major naval construction program aimed at establishing the so-called two-power standard, whereby the Royal Navy would be stronger than the next two largest navies combined.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] The plan saw the construction of the eight *Royal Sovereign*-class battleships, which have been regarded as the first class of battleship that would retrospectively be referred to as "pre-dreadnought battleships".
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] These large battleships incorporated a number of major improvements over earlier vessels like the *Devastation*s, including a high freeboard for true ocean-going capability, more extensive armor protection, heavier secondary battery guns, and greater speed.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] The ships were armed with four 13.5 in (340 mm) guns in two twin mounts, fore and aft, which established the pattern for subsequent battleships.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] After building a trio of smaller second class battleships intended for the colonial empire, Britain followed with the nine-strong *Majestic*-class battleships in 1893–1895, which improved on the basic *Royal Sovereign* design.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] These ships adopted the 12 in (305 mm) gun, which would become the standard for all subsequent British pre-dreadnoughts.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] Foreign navies quickly began pre-dreadnoughts of their own; France began *Brennus* in 1889 and Germany laid down four *Brandenburg*-class battleships in 1890.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] The United States Navy laid down three *Indiana*-class battleships in 1891, the same year work began on the Russian battleship *Tri Sviatitelia*.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] Japan ordered the two *Fuji*-class battleships from British yards, to an improved *Royal Sovereign* design, in 1894.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] The Austro-Hungarian Navy eventually ordered its own pre-dreadnoughts, beginning with the *Habsburg* class in 1899.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] All of these ships carried guns of between 11 and 13.4 in (280 and 340 mm), save the Austro-Hungarian vessels, which, being significantly smaller than the rest, only carried 9.4 in (240 mm) guns.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] They also generally carried a light armament for defense against torpedo boats and other light craft.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] Some ships varied from this general pattern, such as the American *Indiana*s, which carried a heavier secondary battery of 8-inch (203 mm) guns, and the German *Brandenburg*s, which had six 11-inch guns for instead of the usual four heavy guns.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] Many of the early French pre-dreadnoughts, such as *Charles Martel*, carried a mixed heavy armament of two 12-inch and two 10.8-inch (274 mm) guns.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] Pre-dreadnoughts continued the technical innovations of the ironclad throughout the 1890s and early 1900s.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] Compound armor gave way to much stronger Harvey armor developed in the United States in 1890, which was in turn superseded by the German Krupp armor in 1894.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] As armor became stronger, it could be reduced in thickness considerably, which saved weight that could be allocated to other aspects of the ship design, and generally permitted larger and more capable battleships.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] At the same time, the advent of smokeless powder continued the trend begun in the French navy of comparatively smaller guns firing at higher velocities.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] Early on in the pre-dreadnought era, most navies standardized on the 12-inch gun; only Germany remained the significant outlier, relying on 11-inch and even 9.4-inch guns for its pre-dreadnoughts.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] Similarly, later in the pre-dreadnought era, the secondary batteries grew in caliber, usually to 7 to 8 in (178 to 203 mm) guns.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] In the last years of the 19th century and the first years of the 20th, the escalation in the building of battleships became an arms race between Britain and Germany.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] The German naval laws of 1890 and 1898 authorized a fleet of 38 battleships, a vital threat to the balance of naval power.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] Britain answered with further shipbuilding, but by the end of the pre-dreadnought era, British supremacy at sea had markedly weakened.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] In 1883, the United Kingdom had 38 ironclad battleships, twice as many as France and almost as many as the rest of the world put together.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] In 1897, Britain's lead was far smaller due to competition from France, Germany, and Russia, as well as the development of pre-dreadnought fleets in Italy, the United States and Japan.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] The Ottoman Empire, Spain, Sweden, Denmark, Norway, the Netherlands, Chile, and Brazil all had second-rate fleets led by armored cruisers, coastal defence ships or monitors.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] Pre-dreadnought battleships received their first test in combat in the Spanish–American War in 1898 at the Battle of Santiago de Cuba.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] An American squadron that included four pre-dreadnoughts had blockaded a Spanish squadron of four armored cruisers in Santiago de Cuba until 3 July, when the Spanish ships attempted to break through and escape.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] All four cruisers were destroyed in the ensuing engagement, as were a pair of Spanish destroyers, and the American ships received little damage in return.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] The battle seemed to indicate that the mixed batteries of pre-dreadnought battleships were very effective, as the medium-caliber guns had inflicted most of the damage (which reinforced the observations of the Battle of Manila Bay, where only cruisers armed with medium guns had been present).
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] It also led navies around the world to begin working on better solutions for rangefinding in the hope of improving gunnery at longer ranges.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] Conflicting colonial ambitions in Korea and Manchuria led Russia and Japan to the next major use of pre-dreadnoughts in combat.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] During the Russo-Japanese War of 1904–1905, squadrons of battleships engaged in a number of battles, including the Battle of the Yellow Sea and the Battle of Tsushima.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] Naval mines also proved to be a deadly threat to battleships on both sides, sinking the Russian *Petropavlovsk* in March 1904 and the Japanese battleships *Hatsuse* and *Yashima* on the same day in May.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] The action in the Yellow Sea began during a Russian attempt to break out of Port Arthur, which the Japanese under Admiral Tōgō Heihachirō had blockaded.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] The Russians outmaneuvered the Japanese and briefly escaped, but the latter's superior speed allowed them to catch up.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] A 12-inch shell struck the Russian flagship, killing the squadron commander and causing the Russian ships to fall into disarray and retreat back to Port Arthur.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] With night falling, the Japanese broke off and reimposed the blockade.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] At Tsushima, Togo outmaneuvered the Russian Second Pacific Squadron that had been sent to reinforce the Pacific Fleet, and the Japanese battleships quickly inflicted fatal damage with long-range fire from their 12-inch guns.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] In both actions during the Russo-Japanese War, the fleets engaged at longer range (as far as 12,000 yd (11,000 m) at the Yellow Sea), where only their 12-inch guns were effective.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] Only in the final stages of the battle at Tsushima, by which time the Russian fleet had been severely damaged and most of its modern battleships sunk or disabled, did the Japanese fleet close to effective range of their secondary guns, fighting as close as 2,700 yd (2,500 m).
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] The actions, particularly the decisive engagement at Tsushima, demonstrated that the lessons taken from the Spanish–American War were incorrect, and that the large-caliber gun should be the only offensive weapon carried by battleships.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] In the early 1900s, some naval theorists had begun to argue for future battleships to discard the heavy secondary batteries and instead carry only big guns.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] The first prominent example was Vittorio Cuniberti, the chief engineer of the Italian *Regia Marina* (Royal Navy); he published an article in 1903 titled "An Ideal Battleship for the British Navy" in *Jane's Fighting Ships*.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] The Japanese Navy was the first to actually order any of these new ships, beginning with the two *Satsuma*-class battleships in 1904, though due to shortages of 12-inch guns, they were completed with a mix of 12- and 10-inch (254 mm) guns.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] By early 1905, Fisher had converted to the 12-inch gun for his proposed new capital ships, and in March that year, the German Navy had decided to build an all-big-gun battleship for the planned *Nassau* class.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] The American *South Carolina* class was authorized in 1905, but work did not begin until December 1906.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] Though several navies had begun design work on all-big-gun battleships, the first to be completed was the British *Dreadnought*, which had been ordered by Fisher.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] He actually preferred a very large armored cruiser equipped with an all-big-gun armament, which would come to be known as the battlecruiser, and he only included *Dreadnought* in his 1905 construction program to appease naval officers who favored continued battleship building.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] Fisher believed that Britain's security against the French and Russian threats would be better guaranteed by squadrons of fast battlecruisers, three of which were laid down in 1906.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] Regardless of Fisher's intentions, the rapidly changing strategic calculus invalidated his plans and ensured that when the 1906–1907 program was being debated, Germany would be Britain's primary rival, the Royal Navy chose to build three more dreadnoughts instead of further battlecruisers.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] Reactions from the other naval powers was immediate; very few pre-dreadnoughts were built afterward, and in the first seven years of the ensuing arms race, all of the major naval powers either had their own dreadnoughts in service or nearing completion.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] Of these competitions, the Anglo-German race was the most significant, though others took place, such as the South American contest.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] Even naval powers of the second and third rank, such as Spain; Brazil, Chile, and Argentina in South America; and Greece and the Ottoman Empire in the Mediterranean had begun dreadnought programs, either domestically or ordering abroad.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] Technological development continued over the decade that followed *Dreadnought*'s launch.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] Already by 1910, the British had begun the first of the so-called "super-dreadnoughts" that carried significantly more powerful 13.5-inch (340 mm) guns, all on the centerline.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] The United States followed suit in 1911, though increasing the caliber of their guns to 14 inches (356 mm).
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] France adopted a 13.4 in (340 mm) gun for its *Bretagne*-class battleships, laid down in 1912.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] That year, Japan laid down the first of its *Fusō*-class battleships, also armed with a 14-inch main battery.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] The Germans waited until 1913, but skipped directly to 15-inch (381 mm) guns.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] By this time, Britain had led the way to the 15-inch gun with the *Queen Elizabeth* class begun in late 1912.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] But more importantly than the increase of caliber, the *Queen Elizabeth*s were the first completely oil-fired battleships and the first fast battleships.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] At around the same time, the United States introduced the next major innovation in battleship design: the all or nothing armor system in the *Nevada* class laid down in 1912.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] The heaviest possible armor was used to protect the ship's propulsion machinery and ammunition magazines, but intermediate protection was stripped away from non-essential areas, since this mid-weight armor only served to detonate armor-piercing shells.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] By the start of World War I in July 1914, the Royal Navy's Grand Fleet outnumbered the German High Seas Fleet by 21 to 13 in numbers of dreadnought battleships and 4 to 3 in battlecruisers.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] And over the course of the war, Britain would add another 14 dreadnoughts, while Germany completed another 6.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] German strategy presumed that Britain would launch an immediate offensive into the southern North Sea, but the British preferred to establish a distant blockade, which very quickly stopped German maritime trade.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] Both sides were aware that, because of the greater number of British dreadnoughts, a full fleet engagement would be likely to result in a British victory.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] The German strategy was therefore to try to provoke an engagement on their terms: either to induce a part of the Grand Fleet to enter battle alone, or to fight a pitched battle near the German coastline, where friendly minefields, torpedo-boats and submarines could be used to even the odds.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] The British fleet commander, Admiral John Jellicoe, refused to be drawn into unfavorable conditions and enforced the blockade at the English Channel and between Scotland and Norway.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] In the Baltic Sea, Germany found itself in the reverse situation, in an even more lopsided fashion versus its Russian opponent.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] The Russian Baltic Fleet had only four dreadnoughts at the start of the war, so they adopted a purely defensive approach to guard the capital at Petrograd and the northern flank of the Russian army units fighting on the Eastern Front.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] In the Mediterranean Sea, Italy initially remained neutral, despite being a member of the Triple Alliance with Germany and Austria-Hungary, leaving the latter to face the French Navy and British Mediterranean Fleet alone.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] After ensuring the French army units in French North Africa were safely convoyed to France, the French fleet sailed to the Adriatic Sea to blockade the Austro-Hungarian fleet, which refused to leave their fortified bases.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] The French, like the other major European naval commanders, had failed to consider that their opponents would not concede to engaging in battle on terms unfavorable to them.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] The Adriatic quickly turned into another stalemate as the threat of Austro-Hungarian mines and submarines prevented a more aggressive employment of the French fleet.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] The Germans embarked on a number of sweeps into the North Sea and raids on British coastal towns to draw out part of the Grand Fleet, which would be isolated and destroyed.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] These included the raid on Scarborough, Hartlepool and Whitby, where the Germans nearly caught an isolated British battle squadron, but turned away, thinking that it was the entire Grand Fleet.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] This strategy ultimately led to the Battle of Jutland on 31 May – 1 June 1916, the largest clash of battleship fleets.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] The first stage of the battle was fought largely by the two sides' battlecruiser squadrons, though the British were supported by four of the *Queen Elizabeth*-class battleships.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] After both battleship fleets engaged, the British crossed the Germans' "T" twice, but the latter managed to extricate themselves from the action as darkness fell.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] Early on 1 June, the High Seas Fleet had reached port.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] In the course of the fighting, three British battlecruisers were destroyed, as was one German battlecruiser and the old pre-dreadnought *Pommern*.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] Numerous cruisers and destroyers were lost on both sides as well.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] The Germans made two further offensive operations in the months after Jutland.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] The first, which led to the inconclusive action of 19 August, saw one German battleship torpedoed by a British submarine and two British cruisers sunk by German U-boats.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] This incident convinced the British that the risks posed by submarines were too great to send the Grand Fleet into the southern North Sea, barring exceptional circumstances like a German invasion of Britain.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] In the second German operation, which took place on 18–19 October, a German cruiser was damaged by a submarine and the Grand Fleet remained in port.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] By this time, the Germans were similarly convinced of the futility of their attempts to isolate part of the British fleet, and discontinued such raids.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] They instead turned to unrestricted submarine warfare, which resulted in their battleships being reduced to a supporting force that guarded the U-boat bases.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] In the Baltic, the Germans made two attempts to capture the islands in the Gulf of Riga.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] The first came in August 1915, and in the ensuing Battle of the Gulf of Riga, a pair of German dreadnoughts engaged in an artillery duel at long range with the Russian pre-dreadnought *Slava* guarding the minefields that protected the gulf.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] The Germans drove off the Russian ship, cleared the minefield, but by the time they entered the gulf, submarines had reportedly arrived.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] Unwilling to risk the battleships in the shallow, confined waters of the gulf, the Germans retreated.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] The second attempt—Operation Albion—took place in October 1917.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] During the Battle of Moon Sound, another pair of German dreadnoughts damaged *Slava* so badly that she had to be scuttled, and the Germans completed their amphibious assault on the islands.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] The modern units of the French and British fleets in the Mediterranean spent much of the war guarding the entrance to the Adriatic, first based at Malta and later moving to Corfu.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] They saw very little action through the war.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] For their part, the Italians were content to reinforce the blockading force guarding the Adriatic, as they, too, were unwilling to risk their capital ships in the mine and submarine infested waters of the Austrian Littoral.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] Instead, light forces carried out most of the operations.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] Meanwhile, several French and British pre-dreadnoughts were sent to attack the Ottoman defenses guarding the Dardanelles.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] In the ensuing naval operations from February to March 1915, several battleships were sunk or damaged by mines and torpedoes.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] When the fleets failed to break through the defenses, the British and French decided to land at Gallipoli to try to take the fortifications by land; the remaining battleships were thereafter used to provide naval gunfire support.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] This, too, ultimately failed and by January 1916, the British and French withdrew their troops.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] Russian battleships saw more action in the Black Sea against their Ottoman opponents.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] By 1916, the Russians had completed a pair of dreadnoughts in the Black Sea, which severely curtailed Ottoman freedom of maneuver.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] In the course of the war, older pre-dreadnoughts proved to be highly vulnerable to underwater damage, whether by naval mine or ship-launched or submarine-delivered torpedoes.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] HMS *Formidable* was sunk by a German U-boat in the English Channel in 1915.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] At the Dardanelles, HMS *Majestic* was sunk by a German U-boat, HMS *Goliath* was sunk by the Ottoman destroyer *Muavenet-i Milliye*.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] The British *Ocean* and *Irresistible* and the French *Bouvet* were all sunk by mines.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] HMS *Russell* and HMS *Cornwallis* were both sunk by mines in the Mediterranean in 1916 and 1917, respectively.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] HMS *King Edward VII* was similarly mined and sunk off the British coast in 1916, and HMS *Britannia* was sunk by a U-boat in the final days of the war.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] The French *Gaulois* and *Suffren* were sunk by U-boats in 1916, and *Danton* was torpedoed and sunk by a U-boat in 1917.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] At Jutland, the only battleship lost was the old pre-dreadnought *Pommern*, which was torpedoed by a destroyer.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] In contrast, dreadnoughts proved to be much more resilient to underwater attack.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] HMS *Marlborough* was damaged by a torpedo at Jutland, but nevertheless returned to port.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] The German SMS *Westfalen* was torpedoed at the action of 19 August 1916, and SMS *Grosser Kurfürst* and *Kronprinz* were torpedoed by the same submarine in November 1917; all three survived.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] SMS *Bayern* was mined during Operation Albion and remained in action against Russian artillery batteries for some time thereafter.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] Dreadnoughts lost to underwater attack were rare.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] HMS *Audacious* was sunk by a mine in October 1914, the Austro-Hungarian SMS *Szent Istvan* was sunk by Italian MAS boats in June 1918, and five months later, Italian frogmen sank *Viribus Unitis* using a powerful limpet mine.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] In the immediate aftermath of the war, the most modern units of the German fleet was interned at Scapa Flow, where in June 1919, their crews scuttled the fleet to avoid it being handed over to the Allies.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] The remaining dreadnoughts still in German ports were therefore seized as compensation for the scuttled ships.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] The postwar *Reichsmarine* of Weimar Germany was limited to a contingent of eight old pre-dreadnoughts (of which two would be kept in reserve) under the terms of the Treaty of Versailles; new battleships were subject to severe restrictions on size and armament.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] The surviving battleships of Austria-Hungary, the other defeated Central Power, were soon distributed among the Allies, to be broken up.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] While the other major naval powers remained free to build new battleships, most of them were financially crippled after the war.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] The prospect of a renewed naval arms race between the United States, United Kingdom, and Japan, appealed to few politicians in the three countries, and so they concluded the Washington Naval Treaty in 1922, which also included Italy and France.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] The treaty limited the number and size of battleships, and imposed a ten-year building holiday, along with other provisions.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] The treaty also imposed a ratio of 5:5:3 on total displacement of battleships for the US, UK, and Japan, respectively, and it severed the Anglo-Japanese Alliance.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] The only exceptions to the building holiday were for the two British *Nelson*-class battleships, which were permitted to give Britain parity with the latest American and Japanese battleships, which were all armed with 16-inch (406 mm) guns.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] The Washington treaty was followed by a series of other naval treaties, including the First London Naval Treaty (1930) and the Second London Naval Treaty (1936), which both set additional limits on major warships.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] The treaty limitations meant that fewer new battleships were launched in 1919–1939 than in 1905–1914.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] The treaties also inhibited development by imposing upper limits on the weights of ships.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] Designs like the projected British N3-class battleship, the first American *South Dakota* class, and the Japanese *Kii* class—all of which continued the trend to larger ships with bigger guns and thicker armor—never got off the drawing board.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] Those designs which were commissioned during this period were referred to as treaty battleships.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] The collapse of the treaty system began during the negotiations for the Second London Treaty, where Japan demanded parity with Britain and the US, which the latter two flatly rejected.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] Japan withdrew from the treaty system in 1936, though the agreements remained in effect until January 1937.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] As early as 1914, the British Admiral Percy Scott predicted that battleships would soon be made irrelevant by aircraft.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] Between 1916 and 1918, US Admiral William Fullam published a series of papers stating that aircraft would become an independent strike arm of the fleet, and argued that the *Lexington*-class battlecruisers then under construction should be converted to aircraft carriers than scrapped.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] By the end of World War I, aircraft had successfully adopted the torpedo as a weapon.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] In 1921 the Italian general and air theorist Giulio Douhet completed a hugely influential treatise on strategic bombing titled *The Command of the Air*, which foresaw the dominance of air power over conventional military and naval forces.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] In 1921, US General Billy Mitchell used the ex-German dreadnought SMS *Ostfriesland* in a series of bombing tests conducted by the Navy and Army.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] The test involved a series of attacks on the stationary, unmanned ships using low-level, land-based bombers dropping bombs that ranged from 550 to 2,000 pounds (250 to 910 kg).
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] *Ostfriesland* was sunk by the heaviest bombs, though Mitchell broke the rules of the tests and the subsequent report concluded that had the ship been crewed, underway, and firing back at the aircraft, damage control teams aboard *Ostfriesland* could have managed any damage inflicted.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] Mitchell and his supporters nevertheless embarked on a public campaign that falsely claimed that *Ostfriesland* was a super-battleship, and the quick sinking proved that battleships were obsolete.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] Mitchell would eventually be subjected to a court martial, convicted, and discharged from the Army over his insubordinate tactics.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] Naval aviation traces its origin back to the first decade of the 20th century, though early efforts were based on using aircraft to scout for the fleet and help direct gunfire at long range.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] A number of experimental aircraft carriers were employed during World War I, primarily by the Royal Navy, all converted from merchant vessels or existing warships.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] The US Navy completed its first carrier, USS *Langley*, in 1922.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] But aircraft carriers in the 1920s faced a number of challenges to be overcome: aircraft of the day were short-ranged, which meant the carrier had to be very close to the enemy to be able to launch and then recover a strike, which exposed the carriers to attack.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] In addition, the available planes had insufficient power to carry meaningful bomb loads.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] Early naval aviators nevertheless pioneered effective tactics like dive bombing during this period.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] Because the Washington Treaty system precluded the construction of any new battleships until the early 1930s, the major naval powers began a program of modernization for their most effective battleships.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] Britain conducted a series of refits to their *Queen Elizabeth*-class battleships through the 1920s, adding anti-torpedo bulges, additional anti-aircraft guns, and aircraft catapults; further refits in the 1930s increased armor protection and further strengthened their anti-aircraft batteries.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] The *Revenge*-class battleships were less heavily modified during the period.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] The US *Florida*, *Wyoming* class, and *New York* classes received similar treatments in the 1920s, while the *Nevada* and *Pennsylvania* classes received new turbines, additional armor, and more anti-aircraft guns.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] The Japanese similarly updated their *Fusō*, *Ise*, and *Nagato*-class battleships, and rebuilt three of the four *Kongō*-class battlecruisers into fast battleships, albeit with significantly inferior protection compared to the other ships.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] They all also received distinctive pagoda masts.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] *Hiei* was initially disarmed to serve as a training ship under the terms of the Washington Treaty, but was remilitarized in the late 1930s.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] In the 1930s, all four classes were lengthened and had their propulsion systems improved to increase their speeds.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] The French and Italian navies were exempted from the 10-year building holiday, owing to the comparative obsolescence of their battleships; they were permitted to build 70,000 long tons (71,000 t) worth of battleships.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] But the weak economies of both countries led both to defer new construction until Germany began building the *Deutschland* class of heavily armed cruiser at the end of the 1920s.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] This prompted the French to build the *Dunkerque* class of small, fast battleships armed with 13 in (330 mm) guns, which led to a short arms race in Europe in the mid-1930s.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] The Italians responded with the significantly larger and more powerful *Littorio* class, armed with 15-inch guns.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] The French, in turn, began the *Richelieu*-class battleships to counter the *Littorio*s.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] By this time, Nazi Germany had signed the Anglo-German Naval Agreement in 1935, which removed the restrictions imposed by Versailles and pegged German naval strength to 35% of British tonnage.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] This permitted the construction of two *Scharnhorst*-class battleships, which were also a response to the *Dunkerque*s.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] The advent of the *Richelieu*s prompted the Germans to build the two *Bismarck*-class battleships late in the decade.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] The Germans thereafter embarked on the ambitious Plan Z naval construction program, which included a total of eight battleships, of which the *Bismarck*s would be the first two.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] Against the backdrop of European rearmament in the mid-1930s, Britain began planning its first battleship class in a decade: the *King George V* class.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] These were armed with 14-inch guns intended to comply with the terms of the Second London Naval Conference, and they were laid down in 1937.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] The United States began their *North Carolina* class at the same time, and though they were intended to be armed with 14-inch guns, Japan's refusal to agree to the Second London Treaty led the US to invoke a clause of the treaty that allowed an increase to 16-inch guns.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] In 1939, these were followed by the four *South Dakota*-class battleships, and in 1940 by the first of four *Iowa*-class battleships.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p01] For its part, Japan had decided to embark on a program of four very large *Yamato*-class battleships, armed with 18-inch (457 mm) guns, as early as 1934, though work did not begin on the first ship until late 1937.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p02] The German pre-dreadnought *Schleswig-Holstein* fired the first shots of World War II by initiating the bombardment of the Polish garrison at Westerplatte in the early hours on 1 September 1939.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p02] The German *Scharnhorst*-class battleships caught the British carrier HMS *Glorious* off the coast of Norway and sank her during the Norwegian campaign.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p02] In the former action, the British sank a pair of older *Bretagne*-class battleships and the fast battleship *Dunkerque*, though the latter was refloated and repaired.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p02] At Dakar, the French battleship *Richelieu* and other forces fended off the British task force, which resulted in the torpedoing of the battleship HMS *Resolution*, which was severely damaged.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p02] Italy entered the war in June 1940, shortly before the French defeat.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p02] In November, the British launched a nighttime airstrike on the naval base at Taranto; in the Battle of Taranto, Fairey Swordfish torpedo bombers disabled three Italian battleships, though they were subsequently repaired.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p02] Over the next year, Italian and British battleships engaged in a number of inconclusive actions as they contested the supply lines to North Africa.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p02] These included the Battle of Cape Spartivento in November 1940 and the Battle of Cape Matapan in March 1941.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p02] At Matapan, the battleship *Vittorio Veneto* was badly damaged by a Swordfish, though the ship returned to port.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p02] The British battleships *Valiant*, *Warspite*, and *Barham* nevertheless caught a group of three heavy cruisers that evening and destroyed them in a furious, close-range night action.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p02] Convoy battles continued through 1941 and into 1942, with actions such as First and Second Sirte.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p02] By 1943, Italian operations were sharply reduced due to a shortage of fuel, and after the Allied invasion of Italy, the country surrendered, allowing most of its fleet to be interned at Malta.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p02] While on the way, the battleship *Roma* was sunk by a German Fritz X guided glide bomb.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p02] In the meantime, in January 1941, the Germans began to send their few battleships on commerce raiding operations in the Atlantic, starting with the two *Scharnhorst*-class ships in Operation Berlin, which was not particularly successful.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p02] *Bismarck* followed with Operation Rheinübung in May, which resulted in two actions, the Battle of the Denmark Strait and the sinking of *Bismarck*.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p02] During the operation, *Bismarck* was crippled by Swordfish torpedo bombers, which allowed a pair of British battleships to catch and destroy her.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p02] By 1942, the last operational German battleships—*Tirpitz* and *Scharnhorst*—were sent to occupied Norway to serve as a fleet in being to tie down British naval resources and to attack supply convoys to the Soviet Union.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p02] The battleship HMS *Duke of York* eventually sank *Scharnhorst* at the Battle of North Cape in December 1943, and *Tirpitz* was destroyed by British heavy bombers in 1944.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p02] On 7 December 1941, the Japanese launched a surprise attack on the US naval base at Pearl Harbor.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p02] Over the course of two waves of dive-, level- and torpedo bombers, the Japanese sank or destroyed five battleships and inflicted serious damage to the facilities there.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p02] Three days later, land-based Japanese aircraft operating out of French Indochina, then occupied by Japan, caught and sank the British battleship HMS *Prince of Wales* and the battlecruiser HMS *Repulse* off the coast of British Malaya.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p02] Though the Taranto and Pearl Harbor strikes were significant steps toward aircraft replacing the battleship as the primary naval striking arm, the sinking of *Prince of Wales* and *Repulse* marked the first time aircraft had sunk capital ships that were maneuvering and returning fire.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p02] Employment of battleships during the Pacific War was limited by a number of factors.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p02] Japanese strategic doctrine, the *Kantai Kessen*, envisioned a decisive clash of battleships at the end of the war, and so kept most of their battleships in home waters, and only the four *Kongō*s were routinely detached to escort the aircraft carriers of the *Kido Butai*.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p02] For their part, the US kept its surviving pre-war battleships out of action primarily because they were too slow to keep up with the carriers.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p02] Later in the war, they were employed as coastal bombardment vessels.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p02] Nevertheless, American and Japanese battleships saw significant action during the Guadalcanal campaign in 1942, most notably at the Naval Battle of Guadalcanal in November.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p02] There, an American squadron centered on the battleships *Washington* and *South Dakota* intercepted and sank the battleship *Kirishima*, though *South Dakota* received significant damage in return.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p02] As more and more of the American fast battleships entered service from 1942, onward, they were frequently used as escorts for the fast carrier task force that was the US Navy's primary striking arm in its campaign across the central Pacific.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p02] During the Philippines campaign, battleships played a central role during the Battle of Leyte Gulf in October 1944.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p02] The action was one of the largest naval battles in history, which took place over several days and as three Japanese fleets attacked the Allied invasion fleet.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p02] The Japanese battleship *Musashi*, part of Center Force, was sunk by American carrier aircraft during the Battle of Sibuyan Sea on 24 October.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p02] During the Battle of Surigao Strait the following night, several US battleships that had been repaired from the attack on Pearl Harbor defeated the Japanese Southern Force that included a pair of battleships.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p02] Center Force attacked again on 25 October in the Battle off Samar, but was driven off by destroyers and aircraft from several escort carriers.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p02] During the Battle of Okinawa in April 1945, Japan sent *Yamato* as a final suicide mission to attack the landing beaches and attempt to stop the invasion of the island.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p02] American aircraft scored between nine and thirteen torpedo hits and six bomb hits on the ship and sank her.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p02] *Haruna* was sunk by US aircraft off Kure, Japan, in July.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p02] The war ended with the Japanese surrender aboard the battleship USS *Missouri* in September 1945.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p02] After World War II, several navies retained their existing battleships, but most were either placed in their reserve fleets or scrapped outright.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p02] Of their surviving pre-war battleships, most of the American vessels were either scrapped or sunk as target ships by 1948, though the most modern vessels, those of the *Tennessee* and *Maryland* classes, survived until the late 1950s and early 1960s.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p02] One of the earlier vessels, USS *Texas*, was preserved as a museum ship.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p02] The four *King George V*-class ships were all broken up by 1957, Only two battleships—the British HMS *Vanguard* and the French *Jean Bart*—were completed after the war.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p02] *Vanguard* did not long outlast the *King George V*s, being scrapped herself in 1960.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p02] *Jean Bart* (and her sister *Richelieu*) remained in the French fleet's inventory until the early 1960s, when they were discarded.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p02] Three of the six American *North Carolina*- and *South Dakota*-class ships were similarly scrapped in the early 1960s, but the other three—*North Carolina*, *Massachusetts*, and *Alabama*—were retained as museum ships.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p02] With the reduced naval budgets of the immediate postwar period, the US Navy chose to concentrate its resources on its carrier force.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p02] Besides the rise of aircraft carriers as the preeminent naval striking force, the advent of nuclear weapons influenced the decision to abandon large battleship fleets.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p02] In 1946, *Nagato*, which was seized by the US, and four American battleships were used during the Operation Crossroads nuclear weapons tests, though three of the American ships survived the two blasts and were later sunk with conventional weapons.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p02] Of the remaining, smaller battleships fleets, Italy retained its two *Andrea Doria*-class battleships, of 1913 vintage, until the late 1950s and early 1960s, when they were scrapped.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p02] One other battleship, *Giulio Cesare* was taken by the Soviets as reparations and renamed *Novorossiysk*; she was sunk by a mine in the Black Sea on 29 October 1955.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p02] The two surviving *Littorio*-class ships were taken by the US and UK as war reparations and scrapped in the late 1940s.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p02] The Soviets still had a pair of World War I-era battleships—*Parizhskaya Kommuna* and *Gangut*—but they, too, were scrapped in the late 1950s.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p02] The three large South American navies still had a handful of pre-World War I dreadnoughts in service after the war.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p02] Brazil eventually discarded its two *Minas Gerais*-class battleships in the early 1950s; *Argentina* sold its two *Rivadavia*-class battleships in 1956; the last ship in the region, the Chilean *Almirante Latorre*, followed them to the breakers' yard in 1959.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p02] The four *Iowa*-class battleships were the only vessels of the type to see significant combat after World War II.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p02] All four ships were reactivated for gunfire support duties during the Korean War in the early 1950s, and *New Jersey* was also deployed during the Vietnam War in 1968–1969 for the same task.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p02] All four ships were modernized in the early 1980s with Tomahawk cruise missiles, Harpoon anti-ship missiles, and Phalanx CIWS systems, along with the latest radar systems.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p02] They were recommissioned as part of the 600-ship Navy program under President Ronald Reagan.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p02] *New Jersey* next saw action in 1982, bombarding Syrian artillery during the Lebanese Civil War.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p02] *Missouri* and *Wisconsin* took part in Operation Desert Storm against Iraqi forces in 1991, bombarding enemy positions along the coast.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p02] The ships proved to be expensive to operate, and they required thousands of men to keep in service, so *Iowa* and *New Jersey* were already back in reserve by that time, and *Missouri* and *Wisconsin* were also decommissioned by the end of 1991.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p02] All four were struck from the Naval Vessel Register in 1995.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p02] When the last *Iowa*-class ship was finally stricken from the Naval Vessel Registry, no battleships remained in service or in reserve with any navy worldwide.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p02] A number are preserved as museum ships, either afloat or in drydock.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p02] The U.S. has eight battleships on display: *Massachusetts*, *North Carolina*, *Alabama*, *Iowa*, *New Jersey*, *Missouri*, *Wisconsin*, and *Texas*.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p02] *Missouri* and *New Jersey* are museums at Pearl Harbor and Camden, New Jersey, respectively.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p02] *Iowa* is on display as an educational attraction at the Los Angeles Waterfront in San Pedro, California.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p02] *Wisconsin* now serves as a museum ship in Norfolk, Virginia.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p02] *Massachusetts*, which has the distinction of never having lost a man during service, is on display at the Battleship Cove naval museum in Fall River, Massachusetts.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p02] *Texas*, the first battleship turned into a museum, is normally on display at the San Jacinto Battleground State Historic Site, near Houston, but as of 2021 is closed for repairs.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p02] *North Carolina* is on display in Wilmington, North Carolina.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p02] *Alabama* is on display in Mobile, Alabama.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p02] The USS Arizona Memorial was erected over the wreck of *Arizona*, which was sunk during the Pearl Harbor attack in 1941, to commemorate those killed in the raid.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p02] Memorials were also placed to mark the wreck of *Utah*, also sunk during the attack.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p02] The only other 20th-century battleship on display is the Japanese pre-dreadnought *Mikasa*, preserved since 1923.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p02] On 22 December 2025, the United States Navy announced the planned construction of new battleships.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p02] The Trump class will be the first nuclear-powered battleship, and it is planned to carry nuclear-capable cruise missiles, and conventional weapons.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p02] For much of their existence, battleships were the embodiment of sea power.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p02] The American naval officer Alfred Thayer Mahan argued in his seminal 1890 work, *The Influence of Sea Power upon History*, a strong navy was vital to the success of a nation, and control of the seas was a prerequisite for the projection of force.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p02] Conversely, countries with weak navies would inevitably decline.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p02] Mahan argued that the cruiser warfare advocated by the *Jeune Ecole* could never be decisive, and that only fleets of battleships could control sea lanes and enforce blockades of an enemy's coast.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p02] The book proved to be widely influential across the world's navies; it was translated into German in 1896, where it was used to support the German naval expansion program championed by Alfred von Tirpitz.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p02] A Japanese-language translation also appeared in 1896, and it soon became required reading at the Japanese naval academy.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p02] By the end of the decade, Russian, French, Italian, and Spanish versions were produced.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p02] The "fleet in being" in part acts as a deterrent against attack.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p02] The concept underpinned Tirpitz's so-called "risk theory" that was the basis of his program to build a German battle fleet.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p02] Even if the Royal Navy maintained a numerical superiority, the risk that the German fleet would inflict grievous damage even in the case of a British victory would militate against any such battle taking place, and Germany would be free to pursue its global ambitions.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p02] By the 1890s, naval tacticians had developed a number of formations in which to employ battleships.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p02] The most prominent were referred to as "line ahead" and "line abreast".
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p02] The former, the standard tactic during the age of sail, arrayed ships in a single-file line, which emphasized broadside fire.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p02] The latter placed ships side-by-side, which was suited to close-range melees where ramming and torpedoes could be effectively employed; after Tegetthoff's success at Lissa in 1866 used a modified line abreast formation, the tactic enjoyed a period of popularity for several years.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p02] By the 1880s, line-ahead tactics had returned to prominence.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p02] Royal Navy officers devised the tactic referred to as "crossing the T" of an enemy fleet, whereby one fleet steaming in line-ahead formation crossed in front of another line of battleships.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p02] This maneuver would allow one's own battleships to concentrate entire broadsides on the leading enemy ship, while one's opponent could only reply with their forward guns.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p02] Many navies adopted the tactic soon thereafter.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p02] As the threat of underwater attack, including mines and torpedoes, developed after the 1860s, capital ships could no longer maintain close blockades of enemy ports.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p02] This required smaller, faster scouts to observe hostile ports so that an enemy fleet could be brought to battle.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p02] Modern cruisers began to be built in the 1880s for this purpose.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p02] Almost immediately after the invention of the airplane, navies recognized its potential as a reconnaissance unit for the fleet's battleships.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p02] The Austro-Hungarian Navy, then following the *Jeune École* doctrine of the 1870s and 1880s, devised the tactic of placing torpedo boats alongside battleships; these would hide behind the larger ships until gun-smoke obscured visibility enough for them to dart out and fire their torpedoes.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p02] While this tactic was made less effective by the development of smokeless propellant, the threat from more capable torpedo craft (later including submarines) remained.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p02] By the 1890s, the Royal Navy had developed the first destroyers, which were initially designed to intercept and drive off any attacking torpedo boats.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p02] The other major naval powers quickly followed suit with similar vessels of their own.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p02] The presence of battleships had a great psychological and diplomatic impact.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p02] Similar to possessing nuclear weapons in the second half of the 20th century, the ownership of battleships marked a country as a regional or global power, and the ability to build them domestically signified that a country could claim to be a great power.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p02] Even during the Cold War, the psychological impact of a battleship was significant.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p02] In September 1983, when Druze militia in Lebanon's Shouf Mountains fired upon U.S.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p02] Marine peacekeepers, the arrival of USS *New Jersey* stopped the firing.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p02] Gunfire from *New Jersey* later killed militia leaders.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p02] Battleships were the largest and most complex, and hence the most expensive warships of their time; as a result, the value of investment in battleships has always been contested.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p02] As the French politician Etienne Lamy wrote in 1879, "The construction of battleships is so costly, their effectiveness so uncertain and of such short duration, that the enterprise of creating an armored fleet seems to leave fruitless the perseverance of a people".
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p02] The *Jeune École* school of thought of the 1870s and 1880s sought alternatives to the crippling expense and debatable utility of a conventional battlefleet.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p02] It proposed what would nowadays be termed a sea denial strategy, based on fast, long-ranged cruisers for commerce raiding and torpedo boat flotillas to attack enemy ships attempting to blockade French ports.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p02] The ideas of the *Jeune École* were ahead of their time; it was not until the 20th century that efficient mines, torpedoes, submarines, and aircraft were available that allowed similar ideas to be effectively implemented.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/battleship-p02] The determination of powers such as Germany to build battlefleets with which to confront much stronger rivals has been criticized by historians, who emphasize the futility of investment in a battlefleet that has no chance of matching its opponent in an actual battle.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/brest-france] The history of Brest during the Middle Ages is the history of its castle.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/brest-france] By the early modern period, however, Brest had become a military harbour, which Richelieu established in 1631.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/brest-france] Brest subsequently grew around its arsenal until the second part of the 20th century.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/brest-france] Heavily damaged by Allied bombing raids during World War II, the city centre was completely rebuilt after the war.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/brest-france] At the end of the 20th century and the beginning of the 21st century, the deindustrialization of the city was followed by the development of the service sector.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/brest-france] Nowadays, Brest is an important university town with 23,000 students.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/brest-france] Brest's history since the 17th century has been linked to the sea: the *Académie de Marine* (Naval Academy) was founded in 1752 in this city.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/brest-france] The aircraft carrier *Charles de Gaulle* was built there.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/brest-france] Every four years, Brest hosts the international festival of the sea, boats and sailors: it is a meeting of old riggings from around the world (*Les Tonnerres de Brest*).
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/brest-france] In the 4th century AD, Brest was known as *Osismis*, as attested in the *Notitia Dignitatum*.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/brest-france] Breton Latin sources of the early Middle Ages also refer to the settlement as *urbs Ocismorum*, using the old name of the tribe of the Osismii.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/brest-france] The city is then recorded as *Bresta* in 856 AD.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/brest-france] The etymology is uncertain, but it may be related to *bre* ('hill').
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/brest-france] Brest's fortress appears to have remained underdeveloped in the early 11th century.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/brest-france] It was thereafter gradually strengthened by the Breton dukes, and became a key defensive and political stronghold.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/brest-france] In 1196, it sheltered the young Arthur of Brittany.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/brest-france] In the 13th century, Brest became fully integrated into ducal control, when Duke John I purchased the castle, town, and port.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/brest-france] In 1240, Harvey V, Lord of Léon ceded it to John I, Duke of Brittany.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/brest-france] In 1342, John IV, Duke of Brittany surrendered Brest to the English, in whose possession it was to remain until 1397.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/brest-france] This was strategically important to the English as it helped protect their communication with Gascony.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/brest-france] Starting in 1534 Brest and the rest of Brittany become fully part of France as the Province of Brittany.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/brest-france] The advantages of Brest's situation as a seaport town were first recognized by Cardinal Richelieu, who in 1631 constructed a harbour with wooden wharves.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/brest-france] This soon became a base for the French Navy.
[src:henri-dupuy-de-lôme/brest-france] Jean-Baptiste Colbert, finance minister under Louis XIV, rebuilt the wharves in masonry and otherwise improved the harbour.
